115 /**
116  * Process an individual Rexx clause and decide what
117  * type of instruction it represents.
118  *
119  * @return An executable instruction object, or OREF_NULL if
120  * we've reached the end of a code block.
121  */
122 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::nextInstruction()
123 {
124  RexxInstruction *workingInstruction = OREF_NULL;
125  // get the first token of the clause
126  RexxToken *first = nextReal();
127 
128  // a :: at the start of a clause is a directive, which ends this execution
129  // block. Back things up and return null to indicate we've reached the end.
130  if (first->isType(TOKEN_DCOLON))
131  {
132  firstToken();
133  reclaimClause();
134  return OREF_NULL;
135  }
136 
137  // the subTerms list is used for a number of temporary things during
138  // parsing, as well as being a handy place for protecting sets of
139  // objects from garbage collection. Empty this list before parsing
140  // any instruction.
141  subTerms->empty();
142  // empty the term stack also
143  terms->empty();
144  // also clear the stack count for each new instruction
145  currentStack = 0;
146 
147 
148  // ok, now go through the instruction type progression. First check is for
149  // a label.
150  RexxToken *second = nextToken();
151 
152  // a label is a symbol or string immediately followed by a :
153  if (first->isSymbolOrLiteral() && second->isType(TOKEN_COLON))
154  {
155  // not allowed in an interpret instruction
156  if (isInterpret())
157  {
158  syntaxError(Error_Unexpected_label_interpret, first);
159  }
160 
161  // create a new instruction using these two tokens.
162  RexxInstruction *inst = labelNew(first, second);
163  // The colon on a label acts as a clause terminator. If there
164  // are any tokens after the colon, we need to make that the start of
165  // the next clause.
166  second = nextToken();
167 
168  if (!second->isEndOfClause())
169  {
170  // push that token back and trim it to this position. This becomes
171  // the next clause.
172  previousToken();
173  trimClause();
174  reclaimClause();
175  }
176  return inst;
177  }
178 
179  // this is potentially an assignment of the form "symbol = expr"
180  // we still have both the first and second tokens available for testing.
181  if (first->isSymbol())
182  {
183  // "symbol == expr" is considered an error
184  if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_STRICT_EQUAL))
185  {
186  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
187  }
188  // true assignment instruction?
189  if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
190  {
191  return assignmentNew(first);
192  }
193  // this could be a special assignment operator such as "symbol += expr"
194  else if (second->isType(TOKEN_ASSIGNMENT))
195  {
196  return assignmentOpNew(first, second);
197  }
198  }
199 
200  // some other type of instruction we need to skip over the first
201  // term of the instruction to determine the type of clause,
202  // including recognition of keyword instructions
203 
204  // reset to the beginning and parse off the first term (which could be a
205  // message send)
206  firstToken();
207  RexxInternalObject *term = parseMessageTerm();
208  // a lot depends on the nature of the second token
209  second = nextToken();
210 
211  // some sort of recognizable message term? Need to check for the
212  // special cases.
213  if (term != OREF_NULL)
214  {
215  // if parsing the message term consumed everything, this is a message instruction
216  if (second->isEndOfClause())
217  {
218  RexxExpressionMessage *msgTerm = (RexxExpressionMessage *)term;
219 
220  return msgTerm->isDoubleTilde() ? doubleMessageNew(msgTerm) : messageNew(msgTerm);
221  }
222  else if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_STRICT_EQUAL))
223  {
224  // messageterm == something is an invalid assignment
225  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
226  }
227  // messageterm = something is a pseudo assignment
228  else if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
229  {
230  ProtectedObject p(term);
231 
232  // we need an expression following the op token, again, using the rest of the
233  // instruction.
234  RexxInternalObject *subexpression = parseExpression(TERM_EOC);
235  if (subexpression == OREF_NULL)
236  {
237  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
238  }
239  // this is a message assignment
240  return messageAssignmentNew((RexxExpressionMessage *)term, subexpression);
241  }
242  // one of the special operator forms?
243  else if (second->isType(TOKEN_ASSIGNMENT))
244  {
245  ProtectedObject p(term);
246  // we need an expression following the op token
247  RexxInternalObject *subexpression = parseExpression(TERM_EOC);
248  if (subexpression == OREF_NULL)
249  {
250  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
251  }
252  // this is a message assignment
253  return messageAssignmentOpNew((RexxExpressionMessage *)term, second, subexpression);
254  }
255  }
256 
257  // ok, none of the special cases passed....now start the keyword processing
258 
259  // reset again and get the first token
260  firstToken();
261  first = nextToken();
262 
263  // see if we can get an instruction keyword match from the first token
264  InstructionKeyword keyword = first->keyword();
265 
266  if (keyword != KEYWORD_NONE)
267  {
268  // we found something, switch to the appropriate instruction processor.
269  switch (keyword)
270  {
271  // NOP instruction
272  case KEYWORD_NOP:
273  return nopNew();
274  break;
275 
276  // DROP instruction
277  case KEYWORD_DROP:
278  return dropNew();
279  break;
280 
281  // SIGNAL instruction
282  case KEYWORD_SIGNAL:
283  return signalNew();
284  break;
285 
286  // CALL instruction, in all of its forms
287  case KEYWORD_CALL:
288  return callNew();
289  break;
290 
291  // RAISE instruction
292  case KEYWORD_RAISE:
293  return raiseNew();
294  break;
295 
296  // ADDRESS instruction
297  case KEYWORD_ADDRESS:
298  return addressNew();
299  break;
300 
301  // NUMERIC instruction
302  case KEYWORD_NUMERIC:
303  return numericNew();
304  break;
305 
306  // TRACE instruction
307  case KEYWORD_TRACE:
308  return traceNew();
309  break;
310 
311  // DO instruction, all variants
312  case KEYWORD_DO:
313  // the option indicates this is a DO instruction.
314  return createLoop(false);
315  break;
316 
317  // all variants of the LOOP instruction
318  case KEYWORD_LOOP:
319  // the option indicates this is a LOOP instruction.
320  return createLoop(true);
321  break;
322 
323  // EXIT instruction
324  case KEYWORD_EXIT:
325  return exitNew();
326  break;
327 
328  // INTERPRET instruction
329  case KEYWORD_INTERPRET:
330  return interpretNew();
331  break;
332 
333  // PUSH instruction
334  case KEYWORD_PUSH:
335  return pushNew();
336  break;
337 
338  // QUEUE instruction
339  case KEYWORD_QUEUE:
340  return queueNew();
341  break;
342 
343  // REPLY instruction
344  case KEYWORD_REPLY:
345  return replyNew();
346  break;
347 
348  // RETURN instruction
349  case KEYWORD_RETURN:
350  return returnNew();
351  break;
352 
353  // IF instruction
354  case KEYWORD_IF:
355  return ifNew();
356  break;
357 
358  // ITERATE instruction
359  case KEYWORD_ITERATE:
360  return leaveNew(KEYWORD_ITERATE);
361  break;
362 
363  // LEAVE instruction
364  case KEYWORD_LEAVE:
365  return leaveNew(KEYWORD_LEAVE);
366  break;
367 
368  // EXPOSE instruction
369  case KEYWORD_EXPOSE:
370  return exposeNew();
371  break;
372 
373  // FORWARD instruction
374  case KEYWORD_FORWARD:
375  return forwardNew();
376  break;
377 
378  // PROCEDURE instruction
379  case KEYWORD_PROCEDURE:
380  return procedureNew();
381  break;
382 
383  // GUARD instruction
384  case KEYWORD_GUARD:
385  return guardNew();
386  break;
387 
388  // USE instruction
389  case KEYWORD_USE:
390  return useNew();
391  break;
392 
393  // ARG instruction
394  case KEYWORD_ARG:
395  return parseNew(SUBKEY_ARG);
396  break;
397 
398  // PULL instruction
399  case KEYWORD_PULL:
400  return parseNew(SUBKEY_PULL);
401  break;
402 
403  // PARSE instruction
404  case KEYWORD_PARSE:
405  return parseNew(SUBKEY_NONE);
406  break;
407 
408  // SAY instruction
409  case KEYWORD_SAY:
410  return sayNew();
411  break;
412 
413  // OPTIONS instruction
414  case KEYWORD_OPTIONS:
415  return optionsNew();
416  break;
417 
418  // select instruction
419  case KEYWORD_SELECT:
420  return selectNew();
421  break;
422 
423  // WHEN instruction in the context of a SELECT
424  case KEYWORD_WHEN:
425  // this parses as if it was an IF, but creates
426  // a different target instruction.
427  return whenNew();
428  break;
429 
430  // OTEHRWISE in a SELECT
431  case KEYWORD_OTHERWISE:
432  return otherwiseNew(first);
433  break;
434 
435  // ELSE instruction...possibly unexpected.
436  case KEYWORD_ELSE:
437  return elseNew(first);
438  break;
439 
440  // END instruction for some block instruction (DO, LOOP, SELECT, OTHERWISE).
441  case KEYWORD_END:
442  return endNew();
443  break;
444 
445  // THEN instruction. IF processing handles THEN directly. Found
446  // in a naked context like this, we have an invalid THEN.
447  case KEYWORD_THEN:
448  syntaxError(Error_Unexpected_then_then);
449  break;
450 
451  // invalid KEYWORD (should really never happen)
452  default:
453  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "keyword", keyword);
454  break;
455  }
456  }
457  // does not begin with a recognized keyword...this is a "command" instruction.
458  else
459  {
460  // the first token is part of the command, put it back.
461  firstToken();
462  return commandNew();
463  }
464  // should never reach here.
465  return OREF_NULL;
466 }

469 /**
470  * Create a "raw" executable instruction object.
471  * Allocation/creation of instruction objects are handled a
472  * little differently, and goes in stages: 1) Have RexxMemory
473  * allocate a Rexx object of the appropriate size. 2) Set the
474  * object behaviour to be the table for the target instruction.
475  * 3) Call the in-memory new() method on this object using the
476  * RexxInstruction() constructor. This does base initialization
477  * of the object as an instruction object. This version is
478  * returned to the caller, with this instruction anchored in the
479  * parser object to protect it from garbage collection, which is
480  * handy if its constructor needs to allocate any additional
481  * objects.
482  *
483  * Step 4) happens once the caller receives this object
484  * instance. It agains calls the new() in-memory allocator for
485  * the final instruction class. The constructor fills in any
486  * instruction specific information, as well as changing the
487  * object virtual function table to the final version. The
488  * information we set up here will remain untouched.
489  *
490  * @param size The size of the object (can be variable for
491  * some instructions).
492  * @param _behaviour The Rexx object behaviour.
493  * @param type The type identifiers for the instruction
494  * (see RexxToken InstructionKeyword enum).
495  *
496  * @return A newly created instruction object with basic instruction initialization.
497  */
498 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::sourceNewObject(size_t size, RexxBehaviour *_behaviour,
499  InstructionKeyword type)
500 {
501  RexxInternalObject *newObject = new_object(size);
502  newObject->setBehaviour(_behaviour);
503  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstruction(clause, type);
504  currentInstruction = (RexxInstruction *)newObject;
505  return (RexxInstruction *)newObject;
506 }

509 /**
510  * Create a "raw" executable instruction object of variable
511  * size. Allocation/creation of instruction objects are handled
512  * a little differently, and goes in stages: 1) Have RexxMemory
513  * allocate a Rexx object of the appropriate size. 2) Set the
514  * object behaviour to be the table for the target instruction.
515  * 3) Call the in-memory new() method on this object using the
516  * RexxInstruction() constructor. This does base initialization
517  * of the object as an instruction object. This version is
518  * returned to the caller, with this instruction anchored in the
519  * parser object to protect it from garbage collection, which is
520  * handy if its constructor needs to allocate any additional
521  * objects.<p>
522  * Step 4) happens once the caller receives this object
523  * instance. It agains calls the new() in-memory allocator for
524  * the final instruction class. The constructor fills in any
525  * instruction specific information, as well as changing the
526  * object virtual function table to the final version. The
527  * information we set up here will remain untouched.
528  *
529  * @param size The base size of the object type.
530  * @param count The count of extra items to add to the object instance.
531  * @param itemSize The size of the extra items to add.
532  * @param _behaviour The Rexx object behaviour.
533  * @param type The type identifiers for the instruction
534  * (see RexxToken InstructionKeyword enum).
535  *
536  * @return A newly created instruction object with basic instruction initialization.
537  */
538 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::sourceNewObject(size_t size, size_t count, size_t itemSize,
539  RexxBehaviour *_behaviour, InstructionKeyword type)
540 {
541  // for variable size instructions, there is always an extra field at the end of the object
542  // for the first slot allocation. If the count is zero, then we subtract the item size from
543  // the base size. Otherwise, we add count - 1 extra items to the allocation.
544  if (count == 0)
545  {
546  size -= itemSize;
547  }
548  else
549  {
550  size += (count - 1) * itemSize;
551  }
552 
553  // go allocate the actual object.
554  return sourceNewObject(size, _behaviour, type);
555 }

558 /**
559  * Parse an ADDRESS instruction and create an executable instruction object.
560  *
561  * @return An instruction object that can perform this function.
562  */
563 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::addressNew()
564 {
565  RexxInternalObject *dynamicAddress = OREF_NULL;
566  RexxString *environment = OREF_NULL;
567  RexxInternalObject *command = OREF_NULL;
568  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
569  Protected<CommandIOConfiguration> ioConfig;
570 
571  // have something to process? Having nothing is not an error, it
572  // just toggles the environment
573  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
574  {
575  // if this is a symbol or a string, this is the
576  // ADDRESS env [command] form. Otherwise, this is an
577  // implicit ADDRESS VALUE
578  if (!token->isSymbolOrLiteral())
579  {
580  // back up to include this token in the expression
581  previousToken();
582  // and get the expression
583  dynamicAddress = parseExpression(TERM_EOC | TERM_WITH | TERM_KEYWORD);
584  // Now check to see if we ended with the WITH keyword, if so,
585  // we need to create an AddressWithInstruction rather than the
586  // normal AddressInstruction object.
587  token = nextToken();
588  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_WITH)
589  {
590  ioConfig = parseAddressWith();
591  }
592  }
593  else
594  {
595  // could be ADDRESS VALUE (NOTE: Subkeyword also
596  // checks that this is a SYMBOL token.
597  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_VALUE)
598  {
599  // get the value expression
600  dynamicAddress = requiredExpression(TERM_EOC | TERM_WITH | TERM_KEYWORD, Error_Invalid_expression_address);
601  // Now check to see if we ended with the WITH keyword, if so,
602  // we need to create an AddressWithInstruction rather than the
603  // normal AddressInstruction object.
604  token = nextToken();
605  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_WITH)
606  {
607  ioConfig = parseAddressWith();
608  }
609  }
610  else
611  {
612  // this is a constant target
613  environment = token->value();
614  // see if we have the command form
615  token = nextReal();
616  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
617  {
618  // back up and create the expression
619  previousToken();
620  // the command expression could be terminated by a WITH keyword,
621  // in which case, we need to worry about command redirection,
622  // which is a much more complicated parsing process.
623  command = parseExpression(TERM_EOC | TERM_WITH | TERM_KEYWORD);
624  // This could have been ADDRESS env WITH (i.e., no expression)
625  // which is a configuration, not a command.
626 
627  // the bit above will have terminated with either the WITH keyword
628  // or the end of the clause. We know this will return something
629  // for an expression if it started with anything other than WITH,
630  // so the next token is either the symbol WITH or the end of clause
631  // Now check to see if we ended with the WITH keyword, if so,
632  // we end up attaching a configuration rather than the
633  // normal AddressInstruction object.
634  token = nextToken();
635  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_WITH)
636  {
637  ioConfig = parseAddressWith();
638  }
639  }
640  }
641  }
642  }
643 
644  // if we don't have an io config, then use the older instruction version for
645  // program save/restore compatibility
646  if (ioConfig == OREF_NULL)
647  {
648  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(ADDRESS, Address);
649  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionAddress(dynamicAddress, environment, command);
650  return newObject;
651  }
652  else
653  {
654  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(ADDRESS, AddressWith);
655  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionAddressWith(dynamicAddress, environment, command, ioConfig);
656  return newObject;
657  }
658 }

661 /**
662  * Complete processing of an ADDRESS instruction that
663  * has specified WITH I/O redirection.
664  *
665  * @param environment
666  * The already parsed environment string
667  * @param command The expression for the command to issue
668  *
669  * @return A new instruction object.
670  */
671 CommandIOConfiguration* LanguageParser::parseAddressWith()
672 {
673  Protected<CommandIOConfiguration> ioConfig = new CommandIOConfiguration();
674 
675  // step to the next token and start processing
676  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
677 
678  // we must have something after the WITH keyword, otherwise this is an error
679  if (token->isEndOfClause())
680  {
681  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_address_with);
682  }
683 
684  // and check options until we reach the end of the clause
685  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
686  {
687  // all options are symbol names
688  if (!token->isSymbol())
689  {
690  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_address_with);
691  }
692 
693  // map the keyword name to a symbolic identifier.
694  InstructionSubKeyword option = token->subKeyword();
695  switch (option)
696  {
697  // Address env cmd with INPUT
698  case SUBKEY_INPUT:
699  {
700  // not valid if we've had this before
701  if (ioConfig->inputType != RedirectionType::DEFAULT)
702  {
703  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_input);
704  }
705  token = nextReal();
706  // is this specified as NORMAL? we don't parse any further.
707  if (checkRedirectNormal(token))
708  {
709  ioConfig->inputType = RedirectionType::NORMAL;
710  }
711  // need to parse further
712  else
713  {
714  previousToken();
715  parseRedirectOptions(ioConfig->inputSource, ioConfig->inputType);
716  }
717  break;
718  }
719  case SUBKEY_OUTPUT:
720  {
721  // not valid if we've had this before
722  if (ioConfig->outputType != RedirectionType::DEFAULT)
723  {
724  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_output);
725  }
726  token = nextReal();
727  // is this specified as NORMAL? we don't parse any further.
728  if (checkRedirectNormal(token))
729  {
730  ioConfig->outputType = RedirectionType::NORMAL;
731  }
732  else
733  {
734  // backup and parse off the output options and targets
735  previousToken();
736  ioConfig->outputOption = parseRedirectOutputOptions();
737  parseRedirectOptions(ioConfig->outputTarget, ioConfig->outputType);
738  }
739  break;
740  }
741  case SUBKEY_ERROR:
742  {
743  // not valid if we've had this before
744  if (ioConfig->errorType != RedirectionType::DEFAULT)
745  {
746  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_error);
747  }
748  token = nextReal();
749  // is this specified as NORMAL? we don't parse any further.
750  if (checkRedirectNormal(token))
751  {
752  ioConfig->errorType = RedirectionType::NORMAL;
753  }
754  else
755  {
756  // backup and parse off the output options and targets
757  previousToken();
758  ioConfig->errorOption = parseRedirectOutputOptions();
759  parseRedirectOptions(ioConfig->errorTarget, ioConfig->errorType);
760  }
761  break;
762  }
763  default:
764  {
765  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_with_option, token);
766  }
767  }
768  // step to the next token position
769  token = nextReal();
770  }
771  // and return the constructed configuration
772  return ioConfig;
773 }

788 /**
789  * Check for potential APPEND/REPLACE options on an
790  * ADDRESS WITH OUTPUT or ERROR keyword.
791  *
792  * @return The output option (including DEFAULT_REPLACE if
793  * nothing was specified)
794  */
795 OutputOption::Enum LanguageParser::parseRedirectOutputOptions()
796 {
797  // any option must be a symbol. The next token after the
798  // option must also be a symbol, but we'll handle that elsewhere.
799  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
800  if (!token->isSymbol())
801  {
802  // back up and return the default
803  previousToken();
804  return OutputOption::DEFAULT;
805  }
806 
807  // now see if this is one of our keyword values
808  switch (token->subKeyword())
809  {
810  case SUBKEY_REPLACE:
811  return OutputOption::REPLACE;
812 
813  case SUBKEY_APPEND:
814  return OutputOption::APPEND;
815 
816  // probably one of the target type keywords
817  default:
818  // back up and return the default
819  previousToken();
820  return OutputOption::DEFAULT;
821  }
822  return OutputOption::DEFAULT;
823 }

826 /**
827  * Parse the different redirection options on ADDRESS WITH
828  *
829  * @param ioType The type of I/O stream we're redirecting
830  * @param source A reference to the field for the evaluated target
831  *
832  * @param type The type of redirection to apply
833  */
834 void LanguageParser::parseRedirectOptions(RexxInternalObject *&source, RedirectionType::Enum &type)
835 {
836  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
837 
838  // all options are symbol names,
839  if (!token->isSymbol())
840  {
841  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_with_io_option, token);
842  }
843 
844  // now handle the different I/O types.
845  switch (token->subKeyword())
846  {
847  // using a stem variable from the context
848  case SUBKEY_STEM:
849  {
850  type = RedirectionType::STEM_VARIABLE;
851  // this must be followed by a stem variable
852  token = nextReal();
853  if (!token->isStem())
854  {
855  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_after_stem_keyword);
856  }
857  // resolve this to a variable expression type.
858  source = addText(token);
859  break;
860  }
861 
862  // a string stream name. Can be a literal or an expression
863  case SUBKEY_STREAM:
864  {
865  type = RedirectionType::STREAM_NAME;
866 
867  // we use the constant expression syntax here like the
868  // RAISE instruction
869  source = parseConstantExpression();
870  if (source == OREF_NULL)
871  {
872  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_missing_general, GlobalNames::STREAM, GlobalNames::ADDRESS);
873  }
874  break;
875  }
876 
877  // determined by evaluating an expression to an object and figuring
878  // out what to do at run time.
879  case SUBKEY_USING:
880  {
881  type = RedirectionType::USING_OBJECT;
882 
883  // we use the constant expression syntax here like the
884  // RAISE instruction
885  source = parseConstantExpression();
886  if (source == OREF_NULL)
887  {
888  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_missing_general, GlobalNames::USING, GlobalNames::ADDRESS);
889  }
890  break;
891  }
892 
893  default:
894  {
895  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_address_with_io_option, token);
896  }
897  }
898 }

902  * Create a new variable assignment instruction.
903  *
904  * @param target This is the token holding the name of the variable name
905  * for the assignment.
906  *
907  * @return An assignment instruction object.
908  */
909 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::assignmentNew(RexxToken *target)
910 {

912  // really is a variable symbol. This handles raising an error if not valid.
913  needVariable(target);
914  // everything after the "=" is the expression that is as to the variable.
915  // The expression is required.
916  RexxInternalObject *expr = requiredExpression(TERM_EOC, Error_Invalid_expression_assign);
917 
918  // build an instruction object and return it.
919  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(ASSIGNMENT, Assignment);
920  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionAssignment(addVariable(target), expr);
921  return newObject;
922 }

926  * Create a special assignment op of the form "variable (op)= expr".
927  *
928  * @param target The assignment target variable.
929  * @param operation The operator token. classId is TOKEN_ASSIGNMENT, the subclass
930  * is the type of the operation to perform.
931  *
932  * @return The constructed instruction object.
933  */
934 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::assignmentOpNew(RexxToken *target, RexxToken *operation)

937  needVariable(target);

942  RexxVariableBase *variable = addVariable(target);

954 /**
955  * Parse a CALL ON or CALL OFF instruction.
956  *
957  * @param type The target instruction type (CALL_ON or CALL_OFF).
958  *
959  * @return An executable instruction object for te target instruction.
960  */
961 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::callOnNew(InstructionSubKeyword type)
962 {
963  // The processing of the CONDITION name is the same for both CALL ON
964  // and CALL OFF
965 
966  RexxString *labelName;
967  RexxString *conditionName;
968  BuiltinCode builtinIndex = NO_BUILTIN;
969 
970 
971  // we must have a symbol following, otherwise this is an error.
972  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
973  if (!token->isSymbol())
974  {
975  syntaxError(type == SUBKEY_ON ? Error_Symbol_expected_on : Error_Symbol_expected_off);
976  }
977 
978  // get the condition involved
979  ConditionKeyword condType = token->condition();
980  // invalid condition specified? another error.
981  // NOTE: CALL ON only supports a subset of the conditions allowed for SIGNAL ON
982  if (condType == CONDITION_NONE ||
983  condType == CONDITION_PROPAGATE ||
984  condType == CONDITION_SYNTAX ||
985  condType == CONDITION_NOVALUE ||
986  condType == CONDITION_LOSTDIGITS ||
987  condType == CONDITION_NOMETHOD ||
988  condType == CONDITION_NOSTRING)
989  {
990  syntaxError(type == SUBKEY_ON ? Error_Invalid_subkeyword_callon : Error_Invalid_subkeyword_calloff, token);
991  }
992  // USER conditions need a little more work.
993  else if (condType == CONDITION_USER)
994  {
995  // The condition name follows the USER keyword.
996  // This must be a symbol and is required.
997  token = nextReal();
998  if (!token->isSymbol())
999  {
1000  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_user);
1001  }
1002  // get the User condition name. That is the default target for the
1003  // signal trap
1004  labelName = token->value();
1005  // The condition name for this instruction is "USER condition", so
1006  // construct that now and make it a common string (likely used
1007  // other places in the program)
1008  conditionName = commonString(labelName->concatToCstring("USER "));
1009  }
1010  else
1011  {
1012  // this is one of the language defined conditions, use this for both
1013  // the name and the condition...the name
1014  labelName = token->value();
1015  conditionName = labelName;
1016  }
1017 
1018  // IF This is CALL ON, we can have an optional signal target
1019  // specified with the NAME option.
1020  if (type == SUBKEY_ON)
1021  {
1022  // ok, we can have a NAME keyword after this
1023  token = nextReal();
1024  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
1025  {
1026  // keywords are always symbols
1027  if (!token->isSymbol())
1028  {
1029  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_callonname, token);
1030  }
1031  // only subkeyword allowed here is NAME
1032  if (token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_NAME)
1033  {
1034  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_callonname, token);
1035  }
1036  // we need a label name after this as a string or symbol
1037  token = nextReal();
1038  if (!token->isSymbolOrLiteral())
1039  {
1040  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_or_string_name);
1041  }
1042  // this overrides the default label taken from the condition name.
1043  labelName = token->value();
1044  // nothing more permitted after this
1045  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_name);
1046  }
1047  // resolve any potential builtin match...not likely to be used, but it is
1048  // part of the defined search order.
1049  builtinIndex = RexxToken::resolveBuiltin(labelName);
1050  }
1051  else
1052  {
1053  // SIGNAL OFF doesn't have a label name, so make sure this is turned off.
1054  // We use this NULL value to determine which function to perform.
1055  labelName = OREF_NULL;
1056 
1057  // must have the end of clause here.
1058  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_condition);
1059  }
1060 
1061  // create a new instruction object
1062  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(CALL_ON, CallOn);
1063  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionCallOn(conditionName, labelName, builtinIndex);
1064 
1065  // if this is the ON form, we have some end parsing resolution to perform.
1066  if (type == SUBKEY_ON)
1067  {
1068  addReference(newObject);
1069  }
1070  return newObject;
1071 }

1074 /**
1075  * Process a call of the form CALL (expr), which
1076  * has a dynamically determined call target.
1077  *
1078  * @param token The first token of the expression (with the opening paren of the name expression.)
1079  *
1080  * @return A new object for executing this call.
1081  */
1082 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::dynamicCallNew(RexxToken *token)
1083 {
1084  // this is a full expression in parens
1085  RexxInternalObject *targetName = parenExpression(token);
1086  // an expression is required
1087  if (targetName == OREF_NULL)
1088  {
1089  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_call);
1090  }
1091  // process the argument list
1092  size_t argCount = parseArgList(OREF_NULL, TERM_EOC);
1093 
1094  // create a new instruction object
1095  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(CALL_VALUE, DynamicCall, argCount, RexxObject * );
1096  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDynamicCall(targetName, argCount, subTerms);
1097

1099  // add this to the reference list for later processing

1104 /**
1105  * Process a call of the form CALL namespace:name, which is
1106  * restricted to public routines in the named namespace.
1107  *
1108  * @param token The first token of the expression (with the opening paren of the name expression.)
1109  *
1110  * @return A new object for executing this call.
1111  */
1112 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::qualifiedCallNew(RexxToken *token)
1113 {
1114  RexxString *namespaceName = token->value();
1115 
1116  // the colon has already been pulled off...so the next token
1117  // needs to be a symbol
1118 
1119  token = nextToken();
1120  if (!token->isSymbol())
1121  {
1122  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_qualified_call, token);
1123  }
1124 
1125  RexxString *routineName = token->value();
1126 
1127  // process the argument list
1128  size_t argCount = parseArgList(OREF_NULL, TERM_EOC);
1129 
1130  // create a new instruction object
1131  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(CALL_QUALIFIED, QualifiedCall, argCount, RexxObject * );
1132  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionQualifiedCall(namespaceName, routineName, argCount, subTerms);
1133 
1134  // NOTE: The call target has no reliance on the labels because it is always an external
1135  // call. This does not need a resolve step.
1136  return newObject;
1137 }

1139 
1140 /**
1141  * Finish parsing of a CALL instruction. There are 3 distinct
1142  * forms of the Call instruction, with a different execution
1143  * object for each form.
1144  *
1145  * @return An executable call instruction object.
1146  */
1147 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::callNew()
1148 {
1149  BuiltinCode builtin_index;
1150  RexxString *targetName = OREF_NULL;
1151  RexxString *namespaceName = OREF_NULL;
1152  size_t argCount = 0;
1153  bool noInternal = false;
1154 
1155  // get the next token (skipping over any blank) following the CALL keyword
1156  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
1157 
1158  // there must be something here.
1159  if (token->isEndOfClause())
1160  {
1161  /* this is an error */
1162  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_or_string_call);
1163  }
1164  // ok, if this is a symbol, we might have CALL ON or CALL OFF. These get
1165  // processed into a separate instruction type.
1166  else if (token->isSymbol())
1167  {
1168  // we could have a namespace-qualified name here.
1169  RexxToken *next = nextToken();
1170  if (next->isType(TOKEN_COLON))
1171  {
1172  return qualifiedCallNew(token);
1173  }
1174 
1175  // back up one token and try the others
1176  previousToken();
1177 
1178 
1179  // check for a matching subkeyword. ON or OFF are of significance
1180  // here.
1181  InstructionSubKeyword keyword = token->subKeyword();
1182  // one of the special forms, this has its own parsing code.
1183  if (keyword == SUBKEY_ON || keyword == SUBKEY_OFF)
1184  {
1185  return callOnNew(keyword);
1186  }
1187  // This is a normal call instruction. Need to grab the target name and
1188  // parse off the arguments
1189  else
1190  {
1191  targetName = token->value();
1192  // set the builtin index for later resolution steps
1193  builtin_index = token->builtin();
1194  // parse off an argument list
1195  argCount = parseArgList(OREF_NULL, TERM_EOC);
1196  }
1197  }
1198  // call with a string target
1199  else if (token->isLiteral())
1200  {
1201  targetName = token->value();
1202  // set the builtin index for later resolution steps
1203  builtin_index = token->builtin();
1204  // parse off an argument list
1205  argCount = parseArgList(OREF_NULL, TERM_EOC);
1206  // because this uses a string name, the internal label
1207  // search is bypassed.
1208  noInternal = true;
1209  }
1210  // is this call (expr) form?
1211  else if (token->isLeftParen())
1212  {
1213  // this has its own custom instruction object.
1214  return dynamicCallNew(token);
1215  }
1216  // Something unknown...
1217  else
1218  {
1219  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_or_string_call);
1220  }
1221 
1222  // create a new Call instruction. This only handles the simple calls.
1223  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(CALL, Call, argCount, RexxObject * );
1224  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionCall(targetName, argCount, subTerms, builtin_index);
1225 
1226  // add to our references list, but only if this is a form where
1227  // internal calls are allowed.
1228  if (!noInternal)
1229  {
1230  addReference(newObject);
1231  }
1232  return newObject;
1233 }

1254 /**
1255  * Parse and create the variants of a controlled DO/LOOP
1256  * instruction (Loop i = 1 to 5 by 2 for 10). This
1257  * can also include a WHILE or UNTIL modifier (but not both).
1258  *
1259  * @param label Any label obtained from the LABEL keyword.
1260  * @param c A variable name for setting a counter (optional)
1261  * @param nameToken The control variable name token.
1262  *
1263  * @return A constructed instruction object of the appropriate type.
1264  */
1265 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::newControlledLoop(RexxString *label, RexxVariableBase *countVariable, RexxToken *nameToken)
1266 {
1267  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
1268  ControlledLoop control;
1269  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
1270  // track while/until forms
1271  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
1272 
1273 
1274  // the control expressions need to be evaluated in the coded order,
1275  // so we keep a little table of the order used.
1276  int keyslot = 0;
1277  // if this DO/LOOP didn't have a label clause, use the control
1278  // variable name as the loop name.
1279  if (label == OREF_NULL)
1280  {
1281  label = nameToken->value();
1282  }
1283 
1284  // get a retriever to be able to access this token.
1285  control.control = addVariable(nameToken);
1286  // parse off the initial value using the subkeywords as expression terminators
1287  control.initial = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_control);
1288 
1289  // protect on the term stack
1290  pushSubTerm(control.initial);
1291 
1292  // ok, keep looping while we don't have a clause terminator
1293  // because the parsing of the initial expression is terminated by either
1294  // the end-of-clause or DO/LOOP keyword, we know the next token will by
1295  // a symbol if it is not the end.
1296  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
1297 
1298  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
1299  {
1300  // this must be a keyword, so resolve it.
1301  switch (token->subKeyword())
1302  {
1303 
1304  case SUBKEY_BY:
1305  {
1306  // only one per customer
1307  if (control.by != OREF_NULL)
1308  {
1309  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1310  }
1311 
1312  // get the keyword expression, which is required also
1313  control.by = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_by);
1314 
1315  // protect on the term stack
1316  pushSubTerm(control.by);
1317 
1318  // record the processing order
1319  control.expressions[keyslot++] = EXP_BY;
1320  break;
1321  }
1322 
1323  case SUBKEY_TO:
1324  {
1325  // only one per customer
1326  if (control.to != OREF_NULL)
1327  {
1328  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1329  }
1330 
1331  // get the keyword expression, which is required also
1332  control.to = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_to);
1333  // protect on the term stack
1334  pushSubTerm(control.to);
1335 
1336  // record the processing order
1337  control.expressions[keyslot++] = EXP_TO;
1338  break;
1339  }
1340 
1341  case SUBKEY_FOR:
1342  {
1343  // only one per customer
1344  if (control.forCount != OREF_NULL)
1345  {
1346  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1347  }
1348  // get the keyword expression, which is required also
1349  control.forCount = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_for);
1350 
1351  // protect on the term stack
1352  pushSubTerm(control.forCount);
1353 
1354  // record the processing order
1355  control.expressions[keyslot++] = EXP_FOR;
1356  break;
1357  }
1358 
1359  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1360  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1361  {
1362  // step back a token and process the conditional
1363  previousToken();
1364  // this also does not allow anything after the loop conditional
1365  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
1366  break;
1367  }
1368 
1369  // invalid loop subkey (should really never happen)
1370  default:
1371  {
1372  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "loop subkey", token->subKeyword());
1373  break;
1374  }
1375  }
1376  token = nextReal();
1377  }
1378 
1379  // NOTE: We parse until we hit the end of clause or found an error,
1380  // so once we get here, there's no need for any end-of-clause checks.
1381 
1382  // we've parsed everything correctly and we have three potential types of
1383  // loop now. 1) A controlled loop with no conditional, 2) a controlled loop
1384  // with a WHILE condition and 3) a controlled loop with a UNTIL condition.
1385  // The conditionalType variable tells us which form it is, so we can create
1386  // the correct type instruction object.
1387 
1388  switch (conditionalType)
1389  {
1390  // Controlled loop with no extra conditional.
1391  case SUBKEY_NONE:
1392  {
1393  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_CONTROLLED, ControlledDo);
1394  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionControlledDo(label, countVariable, control);
1395  return newObject;
1396  }
1397  // Controlled loop with a WHILE conditional
1398  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1399  {
1400  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_CONTROLLED_WHILE, ControlledDoWhile);
1401  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionControlledDoWhile(label, countVariable, control, conditional);
1402  return newObject;
1403  }
1404  // Controlled loop with an UNTIL conditional.
1405  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1406  {
1407  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_CONTROLLED_UNTIL, ControlledDoUntil);
1408  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionControlledDoUntil(label, countVariable, control, conditional);
1409  return newObject;
1410  }
1411  // invalid controlled loop subkey (should really never happen)
1412  default:
1413  {
1414  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "controlled loop subkey", conditionalType);
1415  break;
1416  }
1417  }
1418  return OREF_NULL; // should never get here.
1419 }
1420 
1421 
1422 /**
1423  * Parse and create the variants of a DO OVER loop instruction.
1424  * This can also include a WHILE or UNTIL modifier (but not
1425  * both).
1426  *
1427  * @param label Any label obtained from the LABEL keyword.
1428  * @param nameToken The control variable name token.
1429  *
1430  * @return A constructed instruction object of the appropriate type.
1431  */
1432 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::newDoOverLoop(RexxString *label, RexxVariableBase *countVariable, RexxToken *nameToken)
1433 {
1434  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
1435  OverLoop control;
1436  ForLoop forLoop;
1437  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
1438 
1439  // track while/until forms
1440  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
1441 
1442  // if this DO/LOOP didn't have a label clause, use the control
1443  // variable name as the loop name.
1444  if (label == OREF_NULL)
1445  {
1446  label = nameToken->value();
1447  }
1448 
1449  // save the control variable retriever
1450  control.control = addVariable(nameToken);
1451  // and get the OVER expression, which is required
1452  control.target = requiredExpression(TERM_OVER, Error_Invalid_expression_over);
1453  // protect this expression from GC
1454  pushSubTerm(control.target);
1455 
1456  // ok, keep looping while we don't have a clause terminator
1457  // because the parsing of the initial expression is terminated by either
1458  // the end-of-clause or DO/LOOP keyword, we know the next token will by
1459  // a symbol if it is not the end.
1460  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
1461 
1462  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
1463  {
1464  // this must be a keyword, so resolve it.
1465  switch (token->subKeyword())
1466  {
1467  case SUBKEY_FOR:
1468  {
1469  // only one per customer
1470  if (forLoop.forCount != OREF_NULL)
1471  {
1472  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1473  }
1474  // get the keyword expression, which is required also
1475  forLoop.forCount = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_for);
1476  // protect from GC
1477  pushSubTerm(forLoop.forCount);
1478  break;
1479  }
1480 
1481  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1482  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1483  {
1484  // step back a token and process the conditional
1485  previousToken();
1486  // this also does not allow anything after the loop conditional
1487  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
1488  break;
1489  }
1490 
1491  // invalid DO OVER loop subkey (should really never happen)
1492  default:
1493  {
1494  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO OVER loop subkey", token->subKeyword());
1495  break;
1496  }
1497  }
1498  token = nextReal();
1499  }
1500 
1501  // NOTE: We parse until we hit the end of clause or found an error,
1502  // so once we get here, there's no need for any end-of-clause checks.
1503 
1504  // we've parsed everything correctly and we have six potential types of
1505  // loop now. 1) A DO OVER loop with no conditional, 2) a DO OVER loop
1506  // with a WHILE condition and 3) a DO OVER loop with a UNTIL condition.
1507  // Each of those forms can also have a FOR modifier.
1508  // The conditionalType variable tells us which form it is, so we can create
1509  // the correct type instruction object, the forControl will tell us if we have a FOR
1510  // expression.
1511 
1512  switch (conditionalType)
1513  {
1514  // DO OVER with no extra conditional.
1515  case SUBKEY_NONE:
1516  {
1517  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1518  {
1519  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER, DoOver);
1520  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOver(label, countVariable, control);
1521  return newObject;
1522  }
1523  else
1524  {
1525  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER_FOR, DoOverFor);
1526  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOverFor(label, countVariable, control, forLoop);
1527  return newObject;
1528  }
1529  }
1530  // DO OVER with a WHILE conditional
1531  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1532  {
1533  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1534  {
1535  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER_WHILE, DoOverWhile);
1536  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOverWhile(label, countVariable, control, conditional);
1537  return newObject;
1538  }
1539  else
1540  {
1541  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER_FOR_WHILE, DoOverForWhile);
1542  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOverForWhile(label, countVariable, control, forLoop, conditional);
1543  return newObject;
1544  }
1545  }
1546  // DO OVER with an UNTIL conditional.
1547  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1548  {
1549  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1550  {
1551  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER_UNTIL, DoOverUntil);
1552  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOverUntil(label, countVariable, control, conditional);
1553  return newObject;
1554  }
1555  else
1556  {
1557  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_OVER_FOR_UNTIL, DoOverForUntil);
1558  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoOverForUntil(label, countVariable, control, forLoop, conditional);
1559  return newObject;
1560  }
1561  }
1562  // invalid DO OVER conditional (should really never happen)
1563  default:
1564  {
1565  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO OVER conditional", conditionalType);
1566  break;
1567  }
1568  }
1569  return OREF_NULL; // should never get here.
1570 }

1573 /**
1574  * Parse and create the variants of a DO WITH loop instruction.
1575  * This can also include a WHILE or UNTIL modifier (but not
1576  * both).
1577  *
1578  * @param label Any label obtained from the LABEL keyword.
1579  *
1580  * @return A constructed instruction object of the appropriate type.
1581  */
1582 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::newDoWithLoop(RexxString *label, RexxVariableBase *countVariable, RexxToken *token)
1583 {
1584  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
1585  WithLoop withLoop;
1586  ForLoop forLoop;
1587  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
1588  // track while/until forms
1589  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
1590 
1591  // we have already parsed over the WITH keyword, so we're looking
1592  // for the INDEX, ITEM, and OVER keywords now. OVER must be after
1593  // INDEX and ITEM, which can be in any order (and only one is needed).
1594 
1595  // these all options are marked by symbols, so keep looping while we have one
1596  while (token->isSymbol())
1597  {
1598  // this must be a keyword, so resolve it.
1599  switch (token->subKeyword())
1600  {
1601  // an index variable
1602  case SUBKEY_INDEX:
1603  {
1604  if (withLoop.indexVar != OREF_NULL)
1605  {
1606  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1607  }
1608 
1609  // this must be a variable token
1610  token = nextReal();
1611 
1612  // save the loopWith variable retriever
1613  withLoop.indexVar = requiredVariable(token, "INDEX");
1614  // get the next token and continue
1615  token = nextReal();
1616  continue;
1617  }
1618 
1619  // an item variable
1620  case SUBKEY_ITEM:
1621  {
1622  if (withLoop.itemVar != OREF_NULL)
1623  {
1624  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1625  }
1626 
1627  // this must be a variable token
1628  token = nextReal();
1629 
1630  // save the loopWith variable retriever
1631  withLoop.itemVar = requiredVariable(token, "ITEM");
1632  // get the next token and continue
1633  token = nextReal();
1634  continue;
1635  }
1636 
1637  default:
1638  {
1639  break;
1640  }
1641  }
1642 
1643  // found a keyword that is not INDEX or ITEM, break out of the loop
1644  break;
1645  }
1646 
1647  // we must have at least one of these loop loopWith variables
1648  if (withLoop.itemVar == OREF_NULL && withLoop.indexVar == OREF_NULL)
1649  {
1650  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_with_no_control);
1651  }
1652 
1653  // the next token needs to be an OVER keyword.
1654  if (!token->isSymbol() || token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_OVER)
1655  {
1656  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_with_no_over);
1657  }
1658 
1659  // and get the OVER expression, which is required
1660  withLoop.supplierSource = requiredExpression(TERM_OVER, Error_Invalid_expression_over);
1661 
1662  // protect this expression from GC
1663  pushSubTerm(withLoop.supplierSource);
1664 
1665  // ok, keep looping while we don't have a clause terminator
1666  // because the parsing of the initial expression is terminated by either
1667  // the end-of-clause or DO/LOOP keyword, we know the next token will by
1668  // a symbol if it is not the end.
1669  token = nextReal();
1670 
1671  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
1672  {
1673  // this must be a keyword, so resolve it.
1674  switch (token->subKeyword())
1675  {
1676  case SUBKEY_FOR:
1677  {
1678  // only one per customer
1679  if (forLoop.forCount != OREF_NULL)
1680  {
1681  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_duplicate, token);
1682  }
1683  // get the keyword expression, which is required also
1684  forLoop.forCount = requiredExpression(TERM_CONTROL, Error_Invalid_expression_for);
1685  // protect from GC
1686  pushSubTerm(forLoop.forCount);
1687  break;
1688  }
1689 
1690  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1691  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1692  {
1693  // step back a token and process the conditional
1694  previousToken();
1695  // this also does not allow anything after the loop conditional
1696  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
1697  break;
1698  }
1699 
1700  // invalid DO WITH conditional (should really never happen)
1701  default:
1702  {
1703  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO WITH conditional", conditionalType);
1704  break;
1705  }
1706  }
1707  token = nextReal();
1708  }
1709 
1710  // NOTE: We parse until we hit the end of clause or found an error,
1711  // so once we get here, there's no need for any end-of-clause checks.
1712 
1713  // we've parsed everything correctly and we have six potential types of
1714  // loop now. 1) A DO WITH loop with no conditional, 2) a DO WITH loop
1715  // with a WHILE condition and 3) a DO WITH loop with a UNTIL condition.
1716  // Each of those forms can also have a FOR modifier.
1717  // The conditionalType variable tells us which form it is, so we can create
1718  // the correct type instruction object, the forControl will tell us if we have a FOR
1719  // expression.
1720 
1721  switch (conditionalType)
1722  {
1723  // DO WITH with no extra conditional.
1724  case SUBKEY_NONE:
1725  {
1726  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1727  {
1728  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH, DoWith);
1729  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWith(label, countVariable, withLoop);
1730  return newObject;
1731  }
1732  else
1733  {
1734  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH_FOR, DoWithFor);
1735  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWithFor(label, countVariable, withLoop, forLoop);
1736  return newObject;
1737  }
1738  }
1739  // DO WITH with a WHILE conditional
1740  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1741  {
1742  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1743  {
1744  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH_WHILE, DoWithWhile);
1745  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWithWhile(label, countVariable, withLoop, conditional);
1746  return newObject;
1747  }
1748  else
1749  {
1750  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH_FOR_WHILE, DoWithForWhile);
1751  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWithForWhile(label, countVariable, withLoop, forLoop, conditional);
1752  return newObject;
1753  }
1754  }
1755  // DO WITH with an UNTIL conditional.
1756  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1757  {
1758  if (forLoop.forCount == OREF_NULL)
1759  {
1760  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH_UNTIL, DoWithUntil);
1761  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWithUntil(label, countVariable, withLoop, conditional);
1762  return newObject;
1763  }
1764  else
1765  {
1766  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_WITH_FOR_UNTIL, DoWithForUntil);
1767  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoWithForUntil(label, countVariable, withLoop, forLoop, conditional);
1768  return newObject;
1769  }
1770  }
1771  // invalid DO WITH conditional (should really never happen)
1772  default:
1773  {
1774  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO WITH conditional", conditionalType);
1775  break;
1776  }
1777  }
1778  return OREF_NULL; // should never get here.
1779 }

1848 /**
1849  * Parse a DO FOREVER loop. This will be either just
1850  * DO FOREVER (most common), but can also have WHILE
1851  * or UNTIL modifiers, which makes them identical to DO
1852  * WHILE and DO UNTIL.
1853  *
1854  * @param label The instruction label.
1855  * @param countVariable
1856  * The optional counter variable.
1857  *
1858  * @return An instruction of the appropriate type.
1859  */
1860 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::parseForeverLoop(RexxString *label, RexxVariableBase *countVariable)
1861 {
1862  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
1863  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
1864 
1865  // track while/until forms
1866  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
1867 
1868  // this also does not allow anything after the loop conditional
1869  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_Invalid_do_forever);
1870 
1871  // NOTE: We parse until we hit the end of clause or found an error,
1872  // so once we get here, there's no need for any end-of-clause checks.
1873 
1874  // we've parsed everything correctly and we have three potential types of
1875  // loop now. 1) FOREVER loop with no conditional, 2) a FOREVER loop
1876  // with a WHILE condition and 3) a FOREVER loop with a UNTIL condition.
1877  // The conditionalType variable tells us which form it is, so we can create
1878  // the correct type instruction object.
1879 
1880  switch (conditionalType)
1881  {
1882  // Straight DO FOREVER
1883  case SUBKEY_NONE:
1884  {
1885  return newLoopForever(label, countVariable);
1886  }
1887  // DO FOREVER with a WHILE conditional...identical to a DO WHILE
1888  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1889  {
1890  return newLoopWhile(label, countVariable, conditional);
1891  }
1892  // DO FOREVER with an UNTIL conditional...identical to a DO UNTIL
1893  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1894  {
1895  return newLoopUntil(label, countVariable, conditional);
1896  }
1897  // invalid DO FOREVER conditional (should really never happen)
1898  default:
1899  {
1900  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO FOREVER conditional", conditionalType);
1901  break;
1902  }
1903  }
1904  return OREF_NULL; // should never get here.
1905 }

1908 /**
1909  * Parse a DO count loop. This will be either just DO count
1910  * (most common), but can also have WHILE or UNTIL modifiers.
1911  *
1912  * @param label The instruction label.
1913  *
1914  * @return An instruction of the appropriate type.
1915  */
1916 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::parseCountLoop(RexxString *label, RexxVariableBase *countVariable)
1917 {
1918  // the For count controller
1919  ForLoop forCount;
1920 
1921  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
1922  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
1923 
1924  // track while/until forms
1925  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
1926 
1927  // we know there is something there, so we will either get an
1928  // expression, or get an error for an invalid expression
1929 
1930  forCount.forCount = parseExpression(TERM_COND);
1931 
1932  // protect on the term stack
1933  pushSubTerm(forCount.forCount);
1934 
1935  // process an additional conditional (NOTE: Because of the
1936  // terminators used for the target expression, the only possibilities
1937  // here are end of clause, a WHILE keyword, or an UNTIL keyword)
1938  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
1939 
1940  // NOTE: We parse until we hit the end of clause or found an error,
1941  // so once we get here, there's no need for any end-of-clause checks.
1942 
1943  // we've parsed everything correctly and we have three potential types of
1944  // loop now. 1) A count loop with no conditional, 2) a count loop
1945  // with a WHILE condition and 3) a count loop with a UNTIL condition.
1946  // The conditionalType variable tells us which form it is, so we can create
1947  // the correct type instruction object.
1948 
1949  switch (conditionalType)
1950  {
1951  // DO count with no extra conditional.
1952  case SUBKEY_NONE:
1953  {
1954  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_COUNT, DoCount);
1955  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoCount(label, countVariable, forCount);
1956  return newObject;
1957  }
1958  // DO count with a WHILE conditional
1959  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
1960  {
1961  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_COUNT_WHILE, DoCountWhile);
1962  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoCountWhile(label, countVariable, forCount, conditional);
1963  return newObject;
1964  }
1965  // DO count with an UNTIL conditional.
1966  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
1967  {
1968  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(LOOP_COUNT_UNTIL, DoCountUntil);
1969  ::new((void *)newObject)RexxInstructionDoCountUntil(label, countVariable, forCount, conditional);
1970  return newObject;
1971  }
1972  // invalid DO count conditional (should really never happen)
1973  default:
1974  {
1975  reportException(Error_Interpretation_switch, "DO count conditional", conditionalType);
1976  break;
1977  }
1978  }
1979  return OREF_NULL; // should never get here.
1980 }

1982 
1983 /**
1984  * Create a new instruction object for a DO or LOOP
1985  * instruction.
1986  *
1987  * @param newDo
1988  * @param isLoop indicates whether this is a DO or a LOOP
1989  * instruction.
1990  *
1991  * @return An appropriate instruction object for the type of block
1992  * construct.
1993  */
1994 RexxInstruction* LanguageParser::createLoop(bool isLoop)
1995 {
1996  // we may need to parse ahead a bit to determine the type of loop, so
1997  // get a reset position before getting next token
1998  size_t currentPosition = markPosition();
1999  // We've already figured out this is either a LOOP or a DO, now we need to
2000  // decode what else is going on.
2001  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2002 
2003  // label parsing is handled here.
2004  RexxString *label = OREF_NULL;
2005  // the counter parsing is also
2006  RexxVariableBase *countVariable = OREF_NULL;
2007 
2008  // before doing anything, we need to test for a "LABEL name" and/or "COUNTER name" before other options. We
2009  // need to make certain we check that the keyword is not being
2010  // used as control variable.
2011  while (token->isSymbol())
2012  {
2013  // potentially a label or a counter. Check the keyword value
2014  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_LABEL || token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_COUNTER)
2015  {
2016  // if we already had COUNTER, this is part of the loop
2017  if (countVariable != OREF_NULL && token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_COUNTER)
2018  {
2019  break;
2020  }
2021  // if we already had LABEL, this is part of the loop
2022  if (label != OREF_NULL && token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_LABEL)
2023  {
2024  break;
2025  }
2026  // if the next token is a symbol, this is a label or counter
2027  RexxToken *name = nextReal();
2028  if (name->isSymbol())
2029  {
2030  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_LABEL)
2031  {
2032  // save the label name.
2033  label = name->value();
2034  }
2035  else
2036  {
2037  // get a retriever to be able to access this token.
2038  countVariable = addVariable(name);
2039  }
2040 
2041  // update the reset position before stepping to the next token
2042  currentPosition = markPosition();
2043  // step to the next token for processing the following parts
2044  token = nextReal();
2045  // if we've had both global options specified, everything else after this
2046  // is part of the loop type.
2047  if (countVariable != OREF_NULL && label != OREF_NULL)
2048  {
2049  break;
2050  }
2051  }
2052  // is this symbol "="? Handle as a controlled loop
2053  else if (name->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
2054  {
2055  // This is a controlled loop, we're all positioned to process this.
2056  return newControlledLoop(label, countVariable, token);
2057  }
2058  // similar to assignment instructions, any equal sign triggers this to
2059  // be a controlled form, even if the the "=" is part of a larger instruction
2060  // such as "==". We give this as an expression error.
2061  else if (name->isSubtype(OPERATOR_STRICT_EQUAL))
2062  {
2063  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, name);
2064  }
2065  else
2066  {
2067  // this is either an end-of-clause or something not a symbol. This is an error.
2068  syntaxError(token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_LABEL ? Error_Symbol_expected_LABEL : Error_Symbol_expected_counter);
2069  }
2070  }
2071  else
2072  {
2073  break;
2074  }
2075  }
2076 
2077 
2078  // Just the single token means this is either a simple DO block or
2079  // a LOOP forever, depending on the type of instruction we're parsing.
2080  if (token->isEndOfClause())
2081  {
2082  // A LOOP instruction with nothing is a LOOP FOREVER.
2083  if (isLoop)
2084  {
2085  return newLoopForever(label, countVariable);
2086  }
2087  else
2088  {
2089  // IF this is just a simple DO, the count variable is not allowed.
2090  if (countVariable != OREF_NULL)
2091  {
2092  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_do_simple_do_counter);
2093  }
2094  return newSimpleDo(label);
2095  }
2096  }
2097 
2098  // we've already handled the control variable version where the variable happens to
2099  // be named LABEL or COUNTER above. We still need to check for this with any other name.
2100  if (token->isSymbol())
2101  {
2102  // this can be a control variable or keyword. We need to look ahead
2103  // to the next token.
2104  RexxToken *second = nextReal();
2105  // similar to assignment instructions, any equal sign triggers this to
2106  // be a controlled form, even if the the "=" is part of a larger instruction
2107  // such as "==". We give this as an expression error.
2108  if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_STRICT_EQUAL))
2109  {
2110  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
2111  }
2112  // ok, now check for the control variable.
2113  else if (second->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
2114  {
2115  // go parse a controlled do loop.
2116  return newControlledLoop(label, countVariable, token);
2117  }
2118  // DO name OVER collection form?
2119  else if (second->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_OVER)
2120  {
2121  // parse and return the DO OVER options
2122  return newDoOverLoop(label, countVariable, token);
2123  }
2124  // WITH INDEX var ITEM var OVER expr....with a potential WHILE or UNTIL modifier
2125  else if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_WITH &&
2126  (second->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_INDEX || second->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_ITEM))
2127  {
2128  return newDoWithLoop(label, countVariable, second);
2129  }
2130  // not a controlled form, but this could be a conditional form.
2131  else
2132  {
2133  // start the parsing process over from the beginning with the first of the
2134  // loop-type tokens
2135  resetPosition(currentPosition);
2136 
2137  token = nextReal();
2138  // now check the other keyword varieties.
2139  switch (token->subKeyword())
2140  {
2141  // FOREVER...this can have either a WHILE or UNTIL modifier.
2142  case SUBKEY_FOREVER: // DO FOREVER
2143  {
2144  return parseForeverLoop(label, countVariable);
2145  }
2146 
2147  // WHILE cond
2148  case SUBKEY_WHILE:
2149  {
2150  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
2151  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
2152 
2153  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
2154 
2155  // step back one token and process the conditional
2156  previousToken();
2157  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
2158  // We know this is WHILE already, so we can create this directly
2159  return newLoopWhile(label, countVariable, conditional);
2160  }
2161 
2162  // DO UNTIL cond
2163  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
2164  {
2165  // a construct to fill in for the instruction.
2166  WhileUntilLoop conditional;
2167 
2168  InstructionSubKeyword conditionalType = SUBKEY_NONE;
2169 
2170  // step back one token and process the conditional
2171  previousToken();
2172  conditional.conditional = parseLoopConditional(conditionalType, Error_None);
2173  // We know this is UNTIL already, so we can create this directly
2174  return newLoopUntil(label, countVariable, conditional);
2175  }
2176 
2177  // not a real DO keyword, probably DO expr form, which can also have
2178  // WHILE or UNTIL modifiers.
2179  default:
2180  // push the first token back
2181  previousToken();
2182  // and go parse this out.
2183  return parseCountLoop(label, countVariable);
2184  }
2185  }
2186  }
2187  // just a DO expr form that doesn't start with a symbol
2188  else
2189  {
2190  // push the first token back
2191  previousToken();
2192  // and go parse this out.
2193  return parseCountLoop(label, countVariable);
2194  }
2195  // should never get here
2196  return OREF_NULL;
2197 }

2344 /**
2345  * Parse and create a new USE LOCAL instruction
2346  *
2347  * @return The configured instruction instance.
2348  */
2349 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::useLocalNew()
2350 {
2351  // not valid in an interpret
2352  if (isInterpret())
2353  {
2354  syntaxError(Error_Translation_use_local_interpret);
2355  }
2356 
2357  // validate the placement at the beginning of the code block...
2358  // the rules are the same as with EXPOSE.
2359  if (!lastInstruction->isType(KEYWORD_FIRST))
2360  {
2361  syntaxError(Error_Translation_use_local);
2362  }
2363 
2364  // switch on auto expose tracking
2365  autoExpose();
2366 
2367  // process the variable list and create an instruction from this.
2368  // There are enough differences from EXPOSE/DROP/PROCEDURE that it is
2369  // easier doing this here.
2370  size_t variableCount = 0;
2371 
2372  // the next real token is the start of the list (after the
2373  // space following the keyword instruction.
2374  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2375 
2376  // while not at the end of the clause, process a list of variables. Note
2377  // that the variable list is optional.
2378  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
2379  {
2380  // generally, these are symbols, but not all symbols are variables.
2381  if (token->isSymbol())
2382  {
2383  // non-variable symbol?
2384  if (token->isSubtype(SYMBOL_CONSTANT))
2385  {
2386  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_variable_number, token);
2387  }
2388  // the dummy period and other dot symbols
2389  else if (token->isSubtype(SYMBOL_DUMMY, SYMBOL_DOTSYMBOL))
2390  {
2391  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_variable_period, token);
2392  }
2393  // we only allow simple variables or stems to be declared local
2394  else if (token->isSubtype(SYMBOL_COMPOUND))
2395  {
2396  syntaxError(Error_Translation_use_local_compound, token);
2397  }
2398 
2399  // ok, get a retriever for the variable and push it on the stack.
2400  pushSubTerm(addVariable(token));
2401  // the GUARD instruction also needs to understand about locals,
2402  // so record this as an explicit local
2403  localVariable(token->value());
2404  // update our return value.
2405  variableCount++;
2406  }
2407  // something unrecognized...we need to issue the message for the instruction.
2408  else
2409  {
2410  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_use_local);
2411  }
2412  // and see if we have more variables
2413  token = nextReal();
2414  }
2415 
2416  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(USE_LOCAL, UseLocal, variableCount, RexxObject *);
2417  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionUseLocal(variableCount, subTerms);
2418  return newObject;

2422 /**
2423  * Parse and create a new FORWARD instruction object.
2424  *
2425  * @return The new instruction object.
2426  */
2427 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::forwardNew()
2428 {
2429  // not permitted in interpret
2430  if (isInterpret())
2431  {
2432  syntaxError(Error_Translation_forward_interpret);
2433  }
2434 
2435  // variables for all of the instruction pieces.
2436  bool returnContinue = false;
2437  RexxInternalObject *target = OREF_NULL;
2438  RexxInternalObject *message = OREF_NULL;
2439  RexxInternalObject *superClass = OREF_NULL;
2440  RexxInternalObject *arguments = OREF_NULL;
2441  ArrayClass *array = OREF_NULL;
2442 
2443  // and start parsing
2444  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2445 
2446  // keep processing keywords until we reach the end of the clause
2447  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
2448  {
2449  // all keywords are symbols, so not finding a symbol is an error
2450  if (!token->isSymbol())
2451  {
2452  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_forward_option, token);
2453  }
2454 
2455  // process each of the options
2456  switch (token->subKeyword())
2457  {
2458  // FORWARD TO expr
2459  case SUBKEY_TO:
2460  {
2461  // can only be specified once
2462  if (target != OREF_NULL)
2463  {
2464  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_to);
2465  }
2466  // get the expression, which is required
2467  target = parseConstantExpression();
2468  if (target == OREF_NULL)
2469  {
2470  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_forward_to);
2471  }
2472  pushSubTerm(target);
2473  break;
2474  }
2475 
2476  // FORWARD CLASS expr
2477  case SUBKEY_CLASS:
2478  {
2479  // have a class override already?
2480  if (superClass != OREF_NULL)
2481  {
2482  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_forward_class);
2483  }
2484  // get the value, which is a required expression
2485  superClass = parseConstantExpression();
2486  if (superClass == OREF_NULL)
2487  {
2488  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_forward_class);
2489  }
2490  pushSubTerm(superClass);
2491  break;
2492  }
2493 
2494  // FORWARD MESSAGE expr
2495  case SUBKEY_MESSAGE:
2496  {
2497  // have a message override already?
2498  if (message != OREF_NULL)
2499  {
2500  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_message);
2501  }
2502  // this is a required expression
2503  message = parseConstantExpression();
2504  if (message == OREF_NULL)
2505  {
2506  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_forward_message);
2507  }
2508  pushSubTerm(message);
2509  break;
2510  }
2511 
2512  // FORWARD ARGUMENTS expr
2513  case SUBKEY_ARGUMENTS:
2514  {
2515  // only one of ARGUMENS or ARRAY allowed
2516  if (arguments != OREF_NULL || array != OREF_NULL)
2517  {
2518  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_arguments);
2519  }
2520  // single, required expression
2521  arguments = parseConstantExpression();
2522  if (arguments == OREF_NULL)
2523  {
2524  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_forward_arguments);
2525  }
2526  break;
2527  }
2528 
2529  // FORWARD ARRAY (expr, expr, ...)
2530  case SUBKEY_ARRAY:
2531  {
2532  // only one of ARRAY ARGUMENTS allowed
2533  if (arguments != OREF_NULL || array != OREF_NULL)
2534  {
2535  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_arguments);
2536  }
2537  // we need a list of expression here...process as an argument array
2538  token = nextReal();
2539  if (!token->isLeftParen())
2540  {
2541  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_raise_list);
2542  }
2543  array = parseArgArray(token, TERM_RIGHT);
2544  break;
2545  }
2546 
2547  // FORWARD CONTINUE
2548  case SUBKEY_CONTINUE:
2549  {
2550  // can only be specified once
2551  if (returnContinue)
2552  {
2553  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_continue);
2554  }
2555  returnContinue = true;
2556  break;
2557  }
2558 
2559  // something invalid
2560  default:
2561  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_forward_option, token);
2562  break;
2563  }
2564  // go process another keyword
2565  token = nextReal();
2566  }
2567  // and create the forward object
2568  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(FORWARD, Forward);
2569  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionForward(target, message, superClass, arguments, array, returnContinue);
2570  return newObject;
2571 }

2573 /**
2574  * Parse and create a guard expression.
2575  *
2576  * @return A constructed executable GUARD instruction.
2577  */
2578 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::guardNew()
2579 {
2580  // not permitted in interpret
2581  if (isInterpret())
2582  {
2583  syntaxError(Error_Translation_guard_interpret);
2584  }
2585 
2586  RexxInternalObject *expression = OREF_NULL;
2587  Protected<ArrayClass> variable_list;
2588  size_t variable_count = 0;
2589 
2590 
2591  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2592 
2593  // first token must be either GUARD ON or GUARD OFF.
2594  if (!token->isSymbol())
2595  {
2596  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_guard, token);
2597  }
2598 
2599  // this tells us which way to set
2600  bool guardOn = false;
2601 
2602  // and figure out which case we have
2603  switch (token->subKeyword())
2604  {
2605  // GUARD OFF
2606  case SUBKEY_OFF:
2607  guardOn = false;
2608  break;
2609 
2610  // GUARD OFF
2611  case SUBKEY_ON:
2612  guardOn = true;
2613  break;
2614 
2615  // anything else is an error
2616  default:
2617  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_guard, token);
2618  break;
2619  }
2620 
2621  // we can have a WHEN expression after this.
2622  token = nextReal();
2623 
2624  // we could have a WHEN expression
2625  if (token->isSymbol())
2626  {
2627  switch (token->subKeyword())
2628  {
2629  // GUARD XXX WHEN expr
2630  case SUBKEY_WHEN:
2631  {
2632  // turn on variable tracking during expression evaluation
2633  setGuard();
2634  // evaluate the WHEN expression, which is required. It is also a logical
2635  // expression, so commas are allowed.
2636  expression = requiredLogicalExpression(TERM_EOC, Error_Invalid_expression_guard);
2637 
2638  // get the guard expression variable list
2639  variable_list = getGuard();
2640  variable_count = variable_list->items();
2641 
2642  // if using GUARD WHEN, we will never wake up if there are
2643  // not at least one object variable accessed.
2644  if (variable_count == 0)
2645  {
2646  syntaxError(Error_Translation_guard_expose);
2647  }
2648  break;
2649  }
2650 
2651  // any other keyword is an error
2652  default:
2653  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_guard_on, token);
2654  break;
2655  }
2656  }
2657  // anything other than the end is an error
2658  else if (!token->isEndOfClause())
2659  {
2660  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_guard_on, token);
2661  }
2662 
2663  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(GUARD, Guard, variable_count, RexxVariableBase *);
2664  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionGuard(expression, variable_list, guardOn);
2665  return newObject;
2666 }

2699 /**
2700  * Create a new IF or WHEN instruction object. These
2701  * share the same implementation class, but get wired
2702  * together differently.
2703  *
2704  * @param type The type of instruction to create.
2705  *
2706  * @return A an executable IF instruction object.
2707  */
2708 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::whenNew()
2709 {
2710  // the top of the queue must be a SELECT instruction, but
2711  // we have TWO varieties of this. The two varieties have different
2712  // expression parsing rules.
2713  RexxInstruction *context = topBlockInstruction();
2714  // no block, this is an error
2715  if (context == OREF_NULL)
2716  {
2717  syntaxError(Error_Unexpected_when_when);
2718  }
2719 
2720  // parsing of the WHEN depends on the type of SELECT we're currently in.
2721  if (context->isType(KEYWORD_SELECT))
2722  {
2723  // ok, get a conditional expression
2724  RexxInternalObject *_condition = requiredLogicalExpression(TERM_IF, Error_Invalid_expression_when);
2725  // protect on the term stack
2726  pushSubTerm(_condition);
2727 
2728  // get to the terminator token for this (likely a THEN, but it could
2729  // be an EOC. We use this to update the end location for the instruction since
2730  // a THEN on the same line would include the THEN (and potentially the following)
2731  // instruction in the instruction location. This ensures we truncate at
2732  // the end of the IF portion.
2733  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2734  previousToken();
2735  // this is really an IF instruction
2736  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(WHEN, If);
2737  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionIf(_condition, token);
2738  return newObject;
2739  }
2740  else if (context->isType(KEYWORD_SELECT_CASE))
2741  {
2742  // ok, get a conditional expression
2743  size_t argCount = parseCaseWhenList(TERM_IF);
2744 
2745  // get to the terminator token for this (likely a THEN, but it could
2746  // be an EOC. We use this to update the end location for the instruction since
2747  // a THEN on the same line would include the THEN (and potentially the following)
2748  // instruction in the instruction location. This ensures we truncate at
2749  // the end of the IF portion.
2750  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
2751  previousToken();

2753  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(WHEN_CASE, CaseWhen, argCount, RexxObject *);
2754  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionCaseWhen(argCount, subTerms, token);

2756  }

2955  * instruction object.

2962  FlagSet<NumericInstructionFlags, 32> _flags;
2963 
2964  // get to the first real token of the instruction
2965  RexxToken *token = nextReal();

2967  // all forms of this start with an instruction sub keyword

2969  {
2970  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_numeric, token);
2971  }

2973  // resolve the subkeyword value
2974  InstructionSubKeyword type = token->subKeyword();
2975

2994  // quite some flavours

2999  // get the next token, skipping any white space
3000  token = nextReal();

3004  // reset to the default for this package
3005  _flags[numeric_form_default] = true;
3006  break;
3007  }
3008  // could be a keyword form
3009  else if (token->isSymbol())

3012  switch (token->subKeyword())
3013  {
3014  // NUMERIC FORM SCIENTIFIC
3015  case SUBKEY_SCIENTIFIC:

3025  // check for extra stuff
3026  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_form);
3027  break;
3028

3030  case SUBKEY_VALUE:
3031  expression = requiredExpression(TERM_EOC, Error_Invalid_expression_form);
3032  break;
3033 
3034  // invalid sub keyword
3035  default:
3036  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_form, token);
3037  break;
3038 
3039  }
3040  }
3041  // Implicit NUMERIC FORM VALUE
3042  else
3043  {
3044  previousToken();
3045  expression = parseExpression(TERM_EOC);
3046  }
3047  break;
3048  }
3049 
3050 
3051  default:
3052  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_numeric, token);
