3095 /**
3096  * Parse a PARSE instruction.
3097  *
3098  * @param argPull Indicates if this is an ARG or PULL operation.
3099  *
3100  * @return An executable instruction object.
3101  */
3102 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::parseNew(InstructionSubKeyword argPull)
3103 {
3104  // initialize the source using our initial call value.
3105  InstructionSubKeyword stringSource = argPull;
3106  FlagSet<ParseFlags, 32> parseFlags;
3107  ProtectedObject sourceExpression;
3108 
3109  // if we're working on one of the short forms, there are no source
3110  // options or other keyword modifiers to worry about. Both of these
3111  // use an uppercase version of the string.
3112  if (argPull != SUBKEY_NONE)
3113  {
3114  parseFlags[parse_upper] = true;
3115  }
3116  // long form, need to figure out the casing and search options + a source
3117  // for where the string comes from.
3118  else
3119  {
3120  InstructionSubKeyword keyword = SUBKEY_NONE;
3121  RexxToken *token;
3122 
3123  // we first need to parse out any of the option modifiers
3124  for (;;)
3125  {
3126  token = nextReal();
3127  // anything not a symbol is an error
3128  if (!token->isSymbol())
3129  {
3130  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_parse);
3131  }
3132 
3133  // resolve this to the indexed form
3134  keyword = token->parseOption();
3135 
3136  switch (keyword)
3137  {
3138  // we only handle the control options here
3139 
3140  // PARSE UPPER ... uppercase the input string(s)
3141  case SUBKEY_UPPER:
3142  // if we've already had an UPPER or LOWER option specified,
3143  // we drop through and handle this like an unknown keyword.
3144  if (parseFlags[parse_upper] || parseFlags[parse_lower])
3145  {
3146  break;
3147  }
3148  // remember the option...passed on when we create the instruction,
3149  // but also helps trap duplicates.
3150  parseFlags[parse_upper] = true;
3151  // go directly to the start of the loop again.
3152  continue;
3153 
3154  // PARSE LOWER ... lowercase the input string(s)
3155  case SUBKEY_LOWER:
3156  // if we've already had an UPPER or LOWER option specified,
3157  // we drop through and handle this like an unknown keyword.
3158  if (parseFlags[parse_upper] || parseFlags[parse_lower])
3159  {
3160  break;
3161  }
3162  // remember the option...passed on when we create the instruction,
3163  // but also helps trap duplicates.
3164  parseFlags[parse_lower] = true;
3165  // go directly to the start of the loop again.
3166  continue;
3167 
3168  // PARSE CASELESS ... all string searches are caseless searches.
3169  case SUBKEY_CASELESS:
3170  // if we've already had a CASELESS option specified,
3171  // we drop through and handle this like an unknown keyword.
3172  if (parseFlags[parse_caseless])
3173  {
3174  break;
3175  }
3176  // remember the option...passed on when we create the instruction,
3177  // but also helps trap duplicates.
3178  parseFlags[parse_caseless] = true;
3179  // go directly to the start of the loop again.
3180  continue;
3181 
3182  // any other option? just fall trough
3183  default:
3184  break;
3185  }
3186 
3187  // if we've reached here, we've found a keyword that is not an option (or rejected
3188  // a keyword because it was a duplicate. Break out of the loop and start handling
3189  // the string source options.
3190  break;
3191  }
3192 
3193  // the last keyword processed above should be our string source,
3194  // now we need to verify.
3195  stringSource = keyword;
3196  switch (keyword)
3197  {
3198  // all of these sources are handled internally by the PARSE instruction. We
3199  // remember what to do, then it is on to parsing the template.
3200  case SUBKEY_PULL:
3201  case SUBKEY_LINEIN:
3202  case SUBKEY_ARG:
3203  case SUBKEY_SOURCE:
3204  case SUBKEY_VERSION:
3205  break;
3206 
3207  // PARSE VAR must be followed by a variable name.
3208  case SUBKEY_VAR:
3209  // must be a symbol, or that is an error.
3210  token = nextReal();
3211  if (!token->isSymbol())
3212  {
3213  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_var);
3214  }
3215 
3216  // get the variable retriever for this.
3217  sourceExpression = addVariable(token);
3218  break;
3219 
3220  // PARSE VALUE expr WITH ... The expression is optional...we'll replace with
3221  // a NULL string if not there.
3222  case SUBKEY_VALUE:
3223  sourceExpression = parseExpression(TERM_WITH | TERM_KEYWORD);
3224  if (sourceExpression.isNull())
3225  {
3226  sourceExpression = GlobalNames::NULLSTRING;
3227  }
3228  // the terminator needs to be a WITH keyword.
3229  token = nextToken();
3230  if (token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_WITH)
3231  {
3232  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_with);
3233  }
3234  break;
3235 
3236  // UNKNOWN (or duplicate) keyword.
3237  default:
3238  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_parse, token);
3239  break;
3240  }
3241  }
3242 
3243  // now we're processing the template(s
3244 
3245  // we create multiple lists here. The different parsing templates are
3246  // pushed on the subTerms stack, while lists of variables are pushed on to the terms
3247  // stack. Referencing them via more descriptive variable names will make this clearer.
3248  QueueClass *parse_template = subTerms;
3249  int templateCount = 0;
3250  QueueClass *_variables = terms;
3251  int variableCount = 0;
3252 
3253  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
3254  for (;;)
3255  {
3256  if (token->isEndOfClause())
3257  {
3258  // we've hit the end of the template, add an END trigger to handle assigning any remaining variables.
3259  // HOWEVER, if there are no variables between the end and the previous trigger, we can
3260  // skip this because there are no variables to assign.
3261  if (variableCount > 0)
3262  {
3263  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(TRIGGER_END, OREF_NULL, variableCount, _variables));
3264  templateCount++;
3265  }
3266  variableCount = 0; // have a new set of variables (well, we're done, really)
3267  break;
3268  }
3269  // comma in the template? Really the same as the end-of-clause case,
3270  // but we need to push a NULL on to the trigger stack to cause a switch to the
3271  // next parse string
3272  else if (token->isComma())
3273  {
3274  if (variableCount > 0)
3275  {
3276  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(TRIGGER_END, OREF_NULL, variableCount, _variables));
3277  templateCount++;
3278  }
3279  // now add an empty fence item to the list...make sure the count is incremented
3280  parse_template->push(OREF_NULL);
3281  templateCount++;
3282  variableCount = 0; // have a new set of variables
3283  }
3284  // some variety of special trigger?
3285  else if (token->isOperator())
3286  {
3287  ParseTriggerType trigger_type = TRIGGER_NONE;
3288  switch (token->subtype())
3289  {
3290  // +num or +(expr) positive relative movement
3291  case OPERATOR_PLUS:
3292  trigger_type = TRIGGER_PLUS;
3293  break;
3294 
3295  // -num or -(expr) form negative relative movement
3296  case OPERATOR_SUBTRACT:
3297  trigger_type = TRIGGER_MINUS;
3298  break;
3299 
3300  // =num or =(expr) absolute column positioning
3301  case OPERATOR_EQUAL:
3302  trigger_type = TRIGGER_ABSOLUTE;
3303  break;
3304 
3305  // <num or <(expr) relative backward movement
3306  case OPERATOR_LESSTHAN:
3307  trigger_type = TRIGGER_MINUS_LENGTH;
3308  break;
3309 
3310  // >num or >(expr)
3311  case OPERATOR_GREATERTHAN:
3312  trigger_type = TRIGGER_PLUS_LENGTH;
3313  break;
3314 
3315  // something unrecognized
3316  default:
3317  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_trigger, token);
3318  break;
3319  }
3320 
3321  // we have an operation. These will be either a numeric symbol
3322  // or an expression in parentheses.
3323  token = nextReal();
3324  if (token->isLeftParen())
3325  {
3326  // parse off an expression in the parens.
3327  ProtectedObject subExpr = parenExpression(token);
3328  // an expression is required
3329  if (subExpr.isNull())
3330  {
3331  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_parse);
3332  }
3333 
3334  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(trigger_type,
3335  subExpr, variableCount, _variables));
3336  variableCount = 0;
3337  templateCount++;
3338  }
3339  // not an expression, we need to find a symbol here.
3340  else if (token->isSymbol())
3341  {
3342  // non variable symbol?
3343  if (token->isVariable())
3344  {
3345  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_position, token);
3346  }
3347 
3348  // add a trigger of the given type.
3349  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(trigger_type,
3350  addText(token), variableCount, _variables));
3351  variableCount = 0;
3352  templateCount++;
3353  }
3354  // something missing following the operator character?
3355  else if (token->isEndOfClause())
3356  {
3357  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_missing);
3358  }
3359  // all other errors go here.
3360  else
3361  {
3362  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_position, token);
3363  }
3364  }
3365  // could be a variable string search using (expr)
3366  else if (token->isLeftParen())
3367  {
3368  // parse off an expression in the parens.
3369  ProtectedObject subExpr = parenExpression(token);
3370  // an expression is required
3371  if (subExpr.isNull())
3372  {
3373  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_parse);
3374  }
3375 
3376  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(parseFlags[parse_caseless] ? TRIGGER_MIXED : TRIGGER_STRING,
3377  subExpr, variableCount, _variables));
3378  variableCount = 0;
3379  templateCount++;
3380  }
3381  // a literal string is a string search.
3382  else if (token->isLiteral())
3383  {
3384 
3385  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(parseFlags[parse_caseless] ? TRIGGER_MIXED : TRIGGER_STRING,
3386  addText(token), variableCount, _variables));
3387  variableCount = 0;
3388  templateCount++;
3389  }
3390  // a symbol in the template? Several possibilities here: 1) a numeric trigger 2)
3391  else if (token->isSymbol())
3392  {
3393  // absolute positioning
3394  if (token->isNumericSymbol())
3395  {
3396  parse_template->push(new (variableCount) ParseTrigger(TRIGGER_ABSOLUTE,
3397  addText(token), variableCount, _variables));
3398  variableCount = 0;
3399 
3400  templateCount++;
3401  }
3402  // probably some sort of variable
3403  else
3404  {
3405  // if this is the placeholder period, push a null item on to the stack
3406  // to mark this variable position as special
3407  if (token->isDot())
3408  {
3409  _variables->push(OREF_NULL);
3410  variableCount++;
3411  }
3412  // we have a variable or a message term to process
3413  else
3414  {
3415  // this is potentially a message term...step back
3416  // and parse as one. This also catches simple variables
3417  previousToken();
3418  RexxInternalObject *term = parseVariableOrMessageTerm();
3419  if (term == OREF_NULL)
3420  {
3421  syntaxError(Error_Variable_expected_PARSE, token);
3422  }
3423  _variables->push(term);
3424  variableCount++;
3425  }
3426  }
3427  }
3428  // something entirely unknown
3429  else
3430  {
3431  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_template_trigger, token);
3432  }
3433  token = nextReal();
3434  }
3435 
3436  // and finally create the instruction from the accumulated information.
3437  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(PARSE, Parse, templateCount, RexxObject *);
3438  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionParse(sourceExpression, stringSource, parseFlags, templateCount, parse_template);
3439  return newObject;
3440 }

3513 {
3514  ArrayClass *arrayItems = OREF_NULL;
3515  RexxInternalObject *rcValue = OREF_NULL;
3516  RexxInternalObject *description = OREF_NULL;
3517  RexxInternalObject *additional = OREF_NULL;
3518  RexxInternalObject *result = OREF_NULL;
3519  FlagSet<RaiseInstructionFlags, 32> flags;
3520 
3521  // ok, get the first TOKEN
3522  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
3523  // the first token is the condition name, and must be a symbol
3524  if (!token->isSymbol())
3525  {
3526  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_raise);
3527  }
3528 
3529  RexxString *_condition = token->value();
3530  // make sure this matches one of the allowed condition names
3531  ConditionKeyword conditionType = token->condition();
3532  switch (conditionType)
3533  {
3534  // FAILURE, ERROR, and SYNTAX are pretty similar. They take an
3535  // argument after the condition keyword.
3536  case CONDITION_FAILURE:
3537  case CONDITION_ERROR:
3538  case CONDITION_SYNTAX:
3539  {
3540  // SYNTAX requires some extra runtime processing, so set a
3541  // flag for that.
3542  if (conditionType == CONDITION_SYNTAX)
3543  {
3544  flags[raise_syntax] = true;
3545  }
3546 
3547  // this is a constant expression form.
3548  rcValue = parseConstantExpression();
3549  // this is required. If not found, use the terminator
3550  // token to report the error location
3551  if (rcValue == OREF_NULL)
3552  {
3553  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, nextToken());
3554  }
3555  // add this to the sub terms queue
3556  pushSubTerm(rcValue);
3557  break;
3558  }
3559 
3560  // Raising a USER condition...this is a two part name.
3561  case CONDITION_USER:
3562  {
3563  token = nextReal();
3564  // next part must by a symbol
3565  if (!token->isSymbol())
3566  {
3567  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_user);
3568  }
3569  // the condition name is actually "USER condition", so construct
3570  // the composite
3571  _condition = token->value();
3572  _condition = _condition->concatToCstring("USER ");
3573  // NB: Common string protects this from garbage collection, so we
3574  // don't need to give it extra protection.
3575  _condition = commonString(_condition);
3576  break;
3577  }
3578 
3579  // no special processing for any of these
3580  case CONDITION_HALT:
3581  case CONDITION_NOMETHOD:
3582  case CONDITION_NOSTRING:
3583  case CONDITION_NOTREADY:
3584  case CONDITION_NOVALUE:
3585  case CONDITION_LOSTDIGITS:
3586  break;
3587 
3588  // we need to remember if this is propagate
3589  case CONDITION_PROPAGATE: /* CONDITION PROPAGATE */
3590  flags[raise_propagate] = true;
3591  break;
3592 
3593  // could be ALL, or could be something completely unknown.
3594  default:
3595  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_raise, token);
3596  break;
3597  }
3598 
3599  // ok, lots of options to process, and we also need to check for dups/mutual exclusions (sigh)
3600 
3601  // process tokens until we hit the end.
3602  token = nextReal();
3603  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
3604  {
3605  // all options are symbol names,
3606  if (!token->isSymbol())
3607  {
3608  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_raiseoption, token);
3609  }
3610 
3611  // map the keyword name to a symbolic identifier.
3612  InstructionSubKeyword option = token->subKeyword();
3613  switch (option)
3614  {
3615  // RAISE .... DESCRIPTION expr
3616  case SUBKEY_DESCRIPTION:
3617  {
3618  // not valid if we've had this before
3619  if (description != OREF_NULL)
3620  {
3621  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_description);
3622  }
3623  // this is constant expression form, and is required
3624  description = parseConstantExpression();
3625  if (description == OREF_NULL)
3626  {
3627  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_raise_description);
3628  }
3629  // protect from GC.
3630  pushSubTerm(description);
3631  break;
3632  }
3633 
3634  // RAISE .... ADDITIONAL expr
3635  case SUBKEY_ADDITIONAL:
3636  {
3637  // can't have dups, and this is mutually exclusive with the ARRAY option.
3638  if (additional != OREF_NULL || arrayItems != OREF_NULL)
3639  {
3640  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_additional);
3641  }
3642  // another constant expression form
3643  additional = parseConstantExpression();
3644  if (additional == OREF_NULL)
3645  {
3646  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_raise_additional);
3647  }
3648  pushSubTerm(additional);
3649  break;
3650  }
3651 
3652  // RAISE ... ARRAY expr
3653  case SUBKEY_ARRAY:
3654  {
3655  // can only specified once, and ARRAY and ADDITIONAL are mutually exclusive
3656  if (additional != OREF_NULL || arrayItems != OREF_NULL)
3657  {
3658  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_additional);
3659  }
3660 
3661  // this is not a conditional expression, the items must be
3662  // surrounded by parens.
3663  token = nextReal();
3664  if (!token->isLeftParen())
3665  {
3666  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_raise_list);
3667  }
3668  // process this like an argument list. Usually, we'd
3669  // leave this on the subTerms stack, but we're pushing
3670  // other items on there that will mess things up. So,
3671  // we grab this in an array.
3672  arrayItems = parseArgArray(token, TERM_RIGHT);
3673  pushSubTerm(arrayItems);
3674  // remember this is the raise form.
3675  flags[raise_array] = true;
3676  break;
3677  }
3678 
3679  // RAISE ... RETURN <expr>
3680  // Two purposes here, specifies EXIT vs RETURN semantics and also
3681  // gives a value for the return.
3682  case SUBKEY_RETURN:
3683  {
3684  // have we hit a RETURN or exit before? This is bad.
3685  if (flags[raise_return] || flags[raise_exit])
3686  {
3687  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_result);
3688  }
3689  // remember which return type we need to use
3690  flags[raise_return] = true;
3691  // and get the return value
3692  result = parseConstantExpression();
3693  // this is actually optional
3694  if (result != OREF_NULL)
3695  {
3696  pushSubTerm(result);
3697  }
3698  break;
3699  }
3700 
3701  // RAISE ... EXIT <expr>
3702  case SUBKEY_EXIT:
3703  {
3704  // check for duplicates
3705  if (flags[raise_return] || flags[raise_exit])
3706  {
3707  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_result);
3708  }
3709  flags[raise_exit] = true;
3710  // get the optional keyword value
3711  result = parseConstantExpression();
3712  if (result != OREF_NULL)
3713  {
3714  pushSubTerm(result);
3715  }
3716  break;
3717  }
3718 
3719  // and invalid subkeyword
3720  default:
3721  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_raiseoption, token);
3722  break;
3723  }
3724  token = nextReal(); /* step to the next keyword */
3725  }
3726 
3727  RexxInstruction *newObject;
3728 
3729  // is this the array version? need to dynamically allocate
3730  if (flags[raise_array])
3731  {
3732  size_t arrayCount = arrayItems->size();
3733  // we pass this as the additional...the flag tells us which to use
3734  additional = arrayItems;
3735  newObject = new_variable_instruction(RAISE, Raise, arrayCount, RexxObject *);
3736  }
3737  // fixed instruction size
3738  else
3739  {
3740  newObject = new_instruction(RAISE, Raise);
3741  }
3742  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionRaise(_condition, rcValue, description, additional, result, flags);
3743  return newObject;
3744 }

3804 /**
3805  * Parse and create a suitable SELECT instruction object.
3806  * This has different objects for standard SELECT and
3807  * SELECT CASE instructions.
3808  *
3809  * @return An executable SELECT instruction object.
3810  */
3811 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::selectNew()
3812 {
3813  // SELECT can be either SELECT; or SELECT CASE. We have different
3814  // classes for the two different functions.
3815  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
3816  RexxString *label = OREF_NULL;
3817  RexxInternalObject *caseExpr = OREF_NULL;
3818 
3819  // ok, if this is more than just SELECT, we need to handle both a LABEL option
3820  // (which must be first) and a potential CASE option, which creates a completely different
3821  // instruction type.
3822  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
3823  {
3824  if (!token->isSymbol())
3825  {
3826  // not a LABEL keyword, this is bad
3827  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_select, token); // SELECT must be followed by the keyword LABEL or CASE
3828  }
3829 
3830  // potentially a label. At this point, not being the label keyword is
3831  // not an error...it could be CASE. We just handle LABEL here.
3832  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_LABEL)
3833  {
3834  // ok, get the label now
3835  token = nextReal();
3836  // this is required, and must be a symbol
3837  if (!token->isSymbol())
3838  {
3839  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_LABEL);
3840  }
3841 
3842  label = token->value();
3843  // step to the next token and handle a potential
3844  // CASE instruction
3845  token = nextReal();
3846  }
3847  // if we have anything left, this must be a CASE option
3848  if (token->isSymbol())
3849  {
3850  // potentially a CASE option. Anything else is an error here
3851  if (token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_CASE)
3852  {
3853  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_select, token); // SELECT must be followed by the keyword LABEL or CASE
3854  }
3855 
3856  // eat the rest of the expression for the CASE, which is
3857  // required
3858  caseExpr = requiredExpression(TERM_EOC, Error_Invalid_expression_select_case);
3859 
3860  // get the terminator token
3861  token = nextReal();
3862  }
3863  // this must be the end token here.
3864  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
3865  {
3866  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_select, token); // SELECT must be followed by the keyword LABEL or CASE
3867  }
3868  }
3869 
3870  // normal SELECT instruction?
3871  if (caseExpr == OREF_NULL)
3872  {
3873  // ok, finally allocate this and return
3874  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(SELECT, Select);
3875  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionSelect(label);
3876  return newObject;
3877  }
3878  // this the SELECT CASE version. Fundamentally a different instruction.
3879  else
3880  {
3881  // ok, finally allocate this and return
3882  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(SELECT_CASE, SelectCase);
3883  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionSelectCase(label, caseExpr);
3884  return newObject;
3885  }
3886 
3887 }

3916 /**
3917  * Complete parsing of a SIGNAL ON or SIGNAL OFF instruction.
3918  * This also has a separate instruction object for executing
3919  * this function.
3920  *
3921  * @param type The keyword type of the ON or OFF function.
3922  *
3923  * @return A new instruction object.
3924  */
3925 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::signalOnNew(InstructionSubKeyword type)
3926 {
3927  // The processing of the CONDITION name is the same for both SIGNAL ON
3928  // and SIGNAL OFF
3929 
3930  RexxString *labelName;
3931  RexxString *conditionName;
3932 
3933  // we must have a symbol following, otherwise this is an error.
3934  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
3935  if (!token->isSymbol())
3936  {
3937  syntaxError(type == SUBKEY_ON ? Error_Symbol_expected_on : Error_Symbol_expected_off);
3938  }
3939 
3940  // get the condition involved
3941  ConditionKeyword condType = token->condition();
3942  // invalid condition specified? another error
3943  if (condType == CONDITION_NONE || condType == CONDITION_PROPAGATE)
3944  {
3945  syntaxError(type == SUBKEY_ON ? Error_Invalid_subkeyword_signalon : Error_Invalid_subkeyword_signaloff, token);
3946  }
3947  // USER conditions need a little more work.
3948  else if (condType == CONDITION_USER)
3949  {
3950  // The condition name follows the USER keyword.
3951  // This must be a symbol and is required.
3952  token = nextReal();
3953  if (!token->isSymbol())
3954  {
3955  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_user);
3956  }
3957  // get the User condition name. That is the default target for the
3958  // signal trap
3959  labelName = token->value();
3960  // The condition name for this instruction is "USER condition", so
3961  // construct that now and make it a common string (likely used
3962  // other places in the program)
3963  conditionName = commonString(labelName->concatToCstring("USER "));
3964  }
3965  else
3966  {
3967  // this is one of the language defined conditions, use this for both
3968  // the name and the condition...the name
3969  labelName = token->value();
3970  conditionName = labelName;
3971  }
3972 
3973  // IF This is signal ON, we can have an optional signal target
3974  // specified with the NAME option.
3975  if (type == SUBKEY_ON)
3976  {
3977  // ok, we can have a NAME keyword after this
3978  token = nextReal();
3979  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
3980  {
3981  // keywords are always symbols
3982  if (!token->isSymbol())
3983  {
3984  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_signalonname, token);
3985  }
3986  // only subkeyword allowed here is NAME
3987  if (token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_NAME)
3988  {
3989  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_subkeyword_signalonname, token);
3990  }
3991  // we need a label name after this as a string or symbol
3992  token = nextReal();
3993  if (!token->isSymbolOrLiteral())
3994  {
3995  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_or_string_name);
3996  }
3997  // this overrides the default label taken from the condition name.
3998  labelName = token->value();
3999  // nothing more permitted after this
4000  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_name);
4001  }
4002  }
4003  else
4004  {
4005  // SIGNAL OFF doesn't have a label name, so make sure this is turned off.
4006  // We use this NULL value to determine which function to perform.
4007  labelName = OREF_NULL;
4008 
4009  // must have the end of clause here.
4010  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_condition);
4011  }
4012 
4013  // create a new instruction object
4014  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(SIGNAL_ON, SignalOn);
4015  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionSignalOn(conditionName, labelName);
4016 
4017  // if this is the ON form, we have some end parsing resolution to perform.
4018  if (type == SUBKEY_ON)
4019  {
4020  addReference(newObject);
4021  }
4022 
4023  return newObject;
4024 }

4027 /**
4028  * Finish parsing a SIGNAL instruction and return
4029  * an appropriate instruction object. The SIGNAL instruction
4030  * performs several distinct functions, so there are 3 separate
4031  * instruction objects tailored to thos functions.
4032  *
4033  * @return An instruction object for processing a SIGNAL.
4034  */
4035 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::signalNew()
4036 {
4037  RexxString *labelName = OREF_NULL; // this is our target label name (default is condition name)
4038 
4039  // now to work.
4040  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
4041  // no target, that's a paddling...
4042  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4043  {
4044  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_or_string_signal);
4045  }
4046  // might be some expression form, which is an implicit SIGNAL VALUE
4047  else if (!token->isSymbolOrLiteral())
4048  {
4049  // step back for the expression processor.
4050  previousToken();
4051  // process this as a dynamic signal instruction
4052  return dynamicSignalNew();
4053  }
4054  else
4055  {
4056  // A static target, although we need to check on the ON/OFF forms.
4057  if (token->isSymbol())
4058  {
4059  // check for a potential subkeyword
4060  InstructionSubKeyword keyword = token->subKeyword();
4061  // SIGNAL ON condition or SIGNAL OFF condition
4062  if (keyword == SUBKEY_ON || keyword == SUBKEY_OFF)
4063  {
4064  // this is a separate instruction form, go handle it.
4065  return signalOnNew(keyword);
4066  }
4067  // explicit VALUE form?
4068  else if (keyword == SUBKEY_VALUE)
4069  {
4070  // process this as a dynamic signal instruction too. Again, we're
4071  // positioned at the correct location for evaluating this.
4072  return dynamicSignalNew();
4073  }
4074  // just an old boring SIGNAL to a label.
4075  else
4076  {
4077  // this is the symbol form
4078  labelName = token->value();
4079  // and nothing is allowed after this
4080  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_signal);
4081  }
4082  }
4083  // SIGNAL with a string target
4084  else
4085  {
4086  labelName = token->value();
4087  // and nothing is allowed after this
4088  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_signal);
4089  }
4090  }
4091 
4092  // create a new instruction object
4093  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(SIGNAL, Signal);
4094  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionSignal(labelName);
4095 
4096  // this requires a resolve call back once the labels are determined.
4097  addReference(newObject);
4098  return newObject;
4099 }

4119 /**
4120  * Parse and create a new Trace instruction object.
4121  *
4122  * @return A Trace instruction object.
4123  */
4124 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::traceNew()
4125 {
4126  TraceSetting settings; // the parsed trace setting flags
4127  bool skipForm = false; // set default trace mode
4128  wholenumber_t debug_skip = 0; // no skipping
4129  RexxInternalObject *expression = OREF_NULL; // not expression form
4130 
4131  // ok, start processing for real
4132  RexxToken *token = nextReal(); // get the next token
4133 
4134  // TRACE by itself is TRACE Normal. Not really highly used
4135  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4136  {
4137  settings.setDefault();
4138  }
4139  else
4140  {
4141  // most trace settings are symbols, but VALUE is a special subkeyword
4142  if (token->isSymbol())
4143  {
4144  // TRACE VALUE expr?
4145  if (token->subKeyword() == SUBKEY_VALUE)
4146  {
4147  // This is a required expression
4148  expression = requiredExpression(TERM_EOC, Error_Invalid_expression_trace);
4149  }
4150  else
4151  {
4152  // we have a symbol here, this should be the trace setting
4153  RexxString *value = token->value();
4154  // and nothing else after the symbol
4155  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_trace);
4156 
4157  // if this is not numeric, this is a TRACE option, with potential
4158  // ? prefix.
4159  if (!value->requestNumber(debug_skip, number_digits()))
4160  {
4161  debug_skip = 0;
4162  char badOption = 0;
4163  // go parse the trace setting values
4164  if (!settings.parseTraceSetting(value, badOption))
4165  {
4166  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_trace_trace, new_string(&badOption, 1));
4167  }
4168  }
4169  // a valid number, this is the skip form
4170  else
4171  {
4172  skipForm = true;
4173  }
4174  }
4175  }
4176  // the trace setting can also be a string
4177  else if (token->isLiteral())
4178  {
4179  RexxString *value = token->value();
4180  // again, that can be the only thing
4181  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_trace);
4182  // same checks as above
4183  if (!value->requestNumber(debug_skip, number_digits()))
4184  {
4185  debug_skip = 0;
4186  char badOption = 0;
4187  // parse into
4188  if (!settings.parseTraceSetting(value, badOption))
4189  {
4190  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_trace_trace, new_string(&badOption, 1));
4191  }
4192  }
4193  else
4194  {
4195  // remember that this is the skip form
4196  skipForm = true;
4197  }
4198  }
4199  // potential numeric value with a sign?
4200  else if (token->isSubtype(OPERATOR_SUBTRACT, OPERATOR_PLUS))
4201  {
4202  // remember that this is the skip form
4203  skipForm = true;
4204 
4205  // we expect to find a number
4206  RexxToken *second = nextReal();
4207  if (second->isEndOfClause())
4208  {
4209  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
4210  }
4211  // this must be a symbol or a literal value
4212  if (!second->isSymbolOrLiteral())
4213  {
4214  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_general, second);
4215  }
4216 
4217  // this needs to be the end of the clause
4218  RexxString *value = second->value();
4219  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_data_trace);
4220 
4221  // convert to a binary number
4222  if (!value->requestNumber(debug_skip, number_digits()))
4223  {
4224  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_whole_number_trace, value);
4225  }
4226 
4227  // minus form? then negate the value
4228  if (token->isSubtype(OPERATOR_SUBTRACT))
4229  {
4230  debug_skip = -debug_skip;
4231  // turns off tracing entirely
4232  }
4233  }
4234  // implicit TRACE VALUE form
4235  else
4236  {
4237  // take a step back and parse the expression
4238  previousToken();
4239  expression = parseExpression(TERM_EOC);
4240  }
4241  }
4242 
4243  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_instruction(TRACE, Trace);
4244  // this is one of three forms
4245  if (skipForm)
4246  {
4247  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionTrace(debug_skip);
4248  }
4249  else if (expression != OREF_NULL)
4250  {
4251  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionTrace(expression);
4252  }
4253  else
4254  {
4255  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionTrace(settings);
4256  }
4257

4259 }

4262 /**
4263  * Parse a USE ARG or USE STRICT ARG instruction.
4264  *
4265  * @return The executable instruction object.
4266  */
4267 RexxInstruction *LanguageParser::useNew()
4268 {
4269  bool strictChecking = false; // no strict checking enabled yet
4270  bool referencesUsed = false; // no aliasing required yet
4271 
4272  // The STRICT keyword turns this into a different instruction with different
4273  // syntax rules
4274  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
4275  InstructionSubKeyword subkeyword = token->subKeyword();
4276 
4277  // check for USE LOCAL first. we really just handle the USE ARG in here
4278  if (subkeyword == SUBKEY_LOCAL)
4279  {
4280  return useLocalNew();
4281  }
4282 
4283  if (subkeyword == SUBKEY_STRICT)
4284  {
4285  token = nextReal(); // skip over the token
4286  strictChecking = true; // apply the strict checks.
4287  }
4288 
4289  // the only subkeyword supported is ARG
4290  if (token->subKeyword() != SUBKEY_ARG)
4291  {
4292  syntaxError(strictChecking == true ? Error_Invalid_subkeyword_use_strict : Error_Invalid_subkeyword_use, token);
4293  }
4294 
4295  // we accumulate 2 sets of data here, so we need 2 queues to push them in
4296  // if this is the SIMPLE version, the second queue will be empty.
4297  size_t variableCount = 0;
4298  Protected<QueueClass> variable_list = new_queue(); // we might be parsing message terms, so we can't use the subterms list.
4299  Protected<QueueClass> defaults_list = new_queue();
4300  token = nextReal(); /* get the next token */
4301 
4302  bool allowOptionals = false; // we don't allow trailing optionals unless the list ends with "..."
4303  // keep processing tokens to the end
4304  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
4305  {
4306  // this could be a token to skip a variable
4307  if (token->isComma())
4308  {
4309  // this goes on as a variable, but an empty entry to process.
4310  // we also need to push empty entries on the other queues to keep everything in sync.
4311  variable_list->push(OREF_NULL);
4312  defaults_list->push(OREF_NULL);
4313  variableCount++;
4314  // step to the next token, and go process more
4315  token = nextReal();
4316  continue;
4317  }
4318  else // something real. This could be a single symbol or a message term
4319  {
4320  // we might have an ellipsis (...) on the end of the list meaning stop argument checking at that point
4321  if (token->isSymbol())
4322  {
4323  // is this an ellipsis symbol?
4324  if (token->value()->strCompare("..."))
4325  {
4326  // ok, this is the end of everything. Tell the instructions to not enforce the max rules
4327  allowOptionals = true;
4328  // but we still need to make sure it's at the end
4329  token = nextReal();
4330  if (!token->isEndOfClause())
4331  {
4332  syntaxError(Error_Translation_use_arg_ellipsis);
4333  }
4334  break; // done parsing
4335  }
4336  }
4337  // this could be a '>' or ',' prefix used to indicate variable aliasing
4338  else if (token->isOperator(OPERATOR_GREATERTHAN) || token->isOperator(OPERATOR_LESSTHAN))
4339  {
4340  // this must be a simple variable symbol or stem symbol
4341  token = nextReal();
4342  if (!token->isSymbol() || !token->isNonCompoundVariable())
4343  {
4344  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_after_use_arg_reference, token);
4345  }
4346 
4347  // get the variable retriever for this variable.
4348  RexxInternalObject *retriever = addText(token);
4349 
4350  // step to the next token, which should be a comma or a end of clause
4351  token = nextReal();
4352  // if this is not a comma, then we need to do some additional checking
4353  if (!token->isComma())
4354  {
4355  // Check to see if a default is specified. This is not
4356  // allowed for references. We could give a generic error, but
4357  // it is better to be explicit about the problem,
4358  if (token->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
4359  {
4360  syntaxError(Error_Translation_use_arg_reference_no_default);
4361  }
4362  // anything other than a end of clause is a generic error
4363  else if (!token->isEndOfClause())
4364  {
4365  // if not an assignment, this needs to be a comma.
4366  syntaxError(Error_Variable_reference_use, token);
4367  }
4368  }
4369  // we had a terminating comma, so step to the next token
4370  else
4371  {
4372  token = nextReal();
4373  }
4374 
4375  // we wrap this in a special retriever to handle the aliasing
4376  Protected<UseArgVariableRef> ref = new UseArgVariableRef((RexxVariableBase *)retriever);
4377 
4378  // add the reference proxy as the variable, and add a NULL to the defaults
4379  // to keep them in sync.
4380  variable_list->push(ref);
4381  defaults_list->push(OREF_NULL);
4382  variableCount++;
4383  // continue the loop. Note that token is already positioned for the
4384  // next section
4385  continue;
4386  }
4387 
4388  previousToken(); // push the current token back for term processing
4389  // see if we can get a variable or a message term from this
4390  RexxInternalObject *retriever = parseVariableOrMessageTerm();
4391  if (retriever == OREF_NULL)
4392  {
4393  syntaxError(Error_Variable_expected_USE, token);
4394  }
4395  variable_list->push(retriever);
4396  variableCount++;
4397  token = nextReal();
4398  // a terminator takes us out. We need to keep our lists in sync with dummy entries.
4399  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4400  {
4401  defaults_list->push(OREF_NULL);
4402  break;
4403  }
4404  // if we've hit a comma here, step to the next token and continue with the next variable
4405  else if (token->isComma())
4406  {
4407  defaults_list->push(OREF_NULL);
4408  token = nextReal();
4409  continue;
4410  }
4411  // if this is NOT a comma, we potentially have a
4412  // default value
4413  if (token->isSubtype(OPERATOR_EQUAL))
4414  {
4415  // this is a constant expression value. Single token forms
4416  // are fine without parens, more complex forms require parens as
4417  // delimiters.
4418  RexxInternalObject *defaultValue = parseConstantExpression();
4419  // not a constant expression is an error
4420  if (defaultValue == OREF_NULL)
4421  {
4422  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_use_arg_default);
4423  }
4424 
4425  // add this to the defaults
4426  defaults_list->push(defaultValue);
4427  // step to the next token
4428  token = nextReal();
4429  // a terminator takes us out.
4430  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4431  {
4432  break;
4433  }
4434  // if we've hit a comma here, step to the next token and continue with the next variable
4435  else if (token->isComma())
4436  {
4437  token = nextReal();
4438  continue;
4439  }
4440  // not a comma is an error
4441  else
4442  {
4443  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_expression_use_arg_default);
4444  }
4445  }
4446  else
4447  {
4448  // if not an assignment, this needs to be a comma.
4449  syntaxError(Error_Variable_reference_use, token);
4450  }
4451  }
4452  }
4453 
4454  RexxInstruction *newObject = new_variable_instruction(USE, Use, variableCount, UseVariable);
4455  ::new ((void *)newObject) RexxInstructionUse(variableCount, strictChecking, allowOptionals, variable_list, defaults_list);
4456 
4457  return newObject;
4458 }

4461 /**
4462  * Process a list of variables for PROCEDURE, DROP, and EXPOSE.
4463  *
4464  * @param type The type of instruction we're parsing for.
4465  *
4466  * @return The count of variables. The variable retrievers are
4467  * pushed onto the subTerm stack.
4468  */
4469 size_t LanguageParser::processVariableList(InstructionKeyword type )
4470 {
4471  size_t listCount = 0;
4472 
4473  // the next real token is the start of the list (after the
4474  // space following the keyword instruction.
4475  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
4476 
4477  // while not at the end of the clause
4478  while (!token->isEndOfClause())
4479  {
4480  // generally, these are symbols, but not all symbols are variables.
4481  if (token->isSymbol())
4482  {
4483  // non-variable symbol?
4484  if (token->isSubtype( SYMBOL_CONSTANT))
4485  {
4486  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_variable_number, token);
4487  }
4488  // the dummy period
4489  else if (token->isSubtype(SYMBOL_DUMMY, SYMBOL_DOTSYMBOL))
4490  {
4491  syntaxError(Error_Invalid_variable_period, token);
4492  }
4493 
4494  // ok, get a retriever for the variable and push it on the stack.
4495  pushSubTerm(addText(token));
4496 
4497  // are we processing an expose instruction? keep track of this variable
4498  // in case we use GUARD WHEN
4499  if (type == KEYWORD_EXPOSE)
4500  {
4501  expose(token->value());
4502  }
4503  // update our return value.
4504  listCount++;
4505  }
4506  // this could be an indirect reference through a list of form "(var)"
4507  else if (token->isLeftParen())
4508  {
4509  listCount++;
4510  // get the next token...which should be a valid variable
4511  token = nextReal();
4512 
4513  if (!token->isSymbol())
4514  {
4515  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_varref);
4516  }
4517 
4518  // get a retriever for the variable in the parens
4519  RexxVariableBase *retriever = addVariable(token);
4520  // and wrap this in a variable reference, which handles the indirection.
4521  retriever = new RexxVariableReference(retriever);
4522  // add this to the queue
4523  subTerms->queue(retriever);
4524 
4525  // make sure we have the closing paren
4526  token = nextReal();
4527  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4528  {
4529  /* report the missing paren */
4530  syntaxError(Error_Variable_reference_missing);
4531  }
4532  // must be a right paren here
4533  else if (!token->isRightParen())
4534  {
4535  syntaxError(Error_Variable_reference_extra, token);
4536  }
4537  }
4538  // something unrecognized...we need to issue the message for the instruction.
4539  else
4540  {
4541  if (type == KEYWORD_DROP)
4542  {
4543  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_drop);
4544  }
4545  else
4546  {
4547  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_expose);
4548  }
4549  }
4550  // and see if we have more variables
4551  token = nextReal();
4552  }
4553 
4554  // we should have at least one variable...
4555  if (listCount == 0)
4556  {
4557  if (type == KEYWORD_DROP)
4558  {
4559  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_drop);
4560  }
4561  else
4562  {
4563  syntaxError(Error_Symbol_expected_expose);
4564  }
4565  }
4566  // return our counter
4567  return listCount;
4568 }

4571 /**
4572  * Allow for WHILE or UNTIL keywords following some other
4573  * looping construct. This returns SUBKEY_WHILE or SUBKEY_UNTIL
4574  * to flag the caller that a conditional has been used.
4575  *
4576  * @param condition_type
4577  * An option pointer for a place to return the condition type (WHILE or UNTIL)
4578  * @param error_message
4579  *
4580  * @return A parsed out expression object.
4581  */
4582 RexxInternalObject *LanguageParser::parseLoopConditional(InstructionSubKeyword &conditionType, RexxErrorCodes error_message)
4583 {
4584  RexxInternalObject *conditional = OREF_NULL;
4585 
4586  // no type detected yet
4587  conditionType = SUBKEY_NONE;
4588 
4589  // get the next token...this should be either EOC or one of WHILE/UNTIL keywords.
4590  RexxToken *token = nextReal();
4591 
4592  // real end of instruction? Nothing to return. This is frequently called
4593  // in situations where we want to check for a trailing conditional
4594  if (token->isEndOfClause())
4595  {
4596  return OREF_NULL;
4597  }
4598 
4599  // if we have a symbol, this is potentially WHILE or UNTIL.
4600  if (token->isSymbol())
4601  {
4602  // get the subkeyword code
4603  switch (token->subKeyword() )
4604  {
4605  // WHILE exprw
4606  case SUBKEY_WHILE: /* DO WHILE exprw */
4607  {
4608  // parse off the conditional. We only recognize other conditional keywords
4609  // as terminators after this. Since we had the keyword, the
4610  // expression is required.
4611  conditional = requiredLogicalExpression(TERM_COND, Error_Invalid_expression_while);
4612  // protect on the term stack
4613  pushSubTerm(conditional);
4614 
4615  // must not be anything after this
4616  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_do_whileuntil);
4617  // and record the type.
4618  conditionType = SUBKEY_WHILE;
4619  break;
4620  }
4621 
4622  // UNTIL expru
4623  case SUBKEY_UNTIL:
4624  {
4625  // pretty much the same as the WHILE situation
4626  conditional = requiredLogicalExpression(TERM_COND, Error_Invalid_expression_until);
4627  // protect on the term stack
4628  pushSubTerm(conditional);
4629 
4630  // must not be anything after this
4631  requiredEndOfClause(Error_Invalid_do_whileuntil);
4632  // and record the type.
4633  conditionType = SUBKEY_UNTIL;
4634  break;
4635  }
4636 
4637  // nothing else is valid here.
4638  default:
4639  syntaxError(error_message, token);
4640  break;
4641  }
4642  }
4643  else
4644  {
4645  // not a symbol, this is invalid
4646  syntaxError(error_message, token);
4647  }
4648 
4649  return conditional;
4650 }
